{"term": "1956", "caseName": "Watkins v. United States", "caseLink": "https://www.oyez.org/cases/1956/261", "caseTranscripts": [{"transcriptTitle": "Oral Argument - March 07, 1957 (Part 2)", "transcriptLink": "https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren5/oral_argument_audio/13305", "transcript": [{"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "As we -- from Justice Frankfurter, I'd like to make it very clear the Government's position about that.", "start": 0, "stop": 11.912, "duration": 11.91}, {"text": "The question was whether or not this was possibly a device or means to avoid further inquiry to the petitioner, and I want to make it clear that the Government does not claim anything of that kind.", "start": 11.912, "stop": 28.619, "duration": 16.71}, {"text": "It could accomplish that purpose just as well if it was so intended but we do not so charge him and there is nothing in the record to give such an implication.", "start": 28.619, "stop": 43.245, "duration": 14.63}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "But my question had an implication, went a little beyond that, whether the kind of relevancies that you sketched or outlined before lunch.", "start": 43.245, "stop": 55.194, "duration": 11.95}, {"text": "Whether the inquiries which you indicated would be relevant to what had preceded.", "start": 55.194, "stop": 62.356, "duration": 7.16}, {"text": "Whether he wasn't fore coming in dealing with questions addressed to him, so far as his conduct and his relation and his knowledge was concerned sort of inquiry with these other people?", "start": 62.356, "stop": 77.03, "duration": 14.67}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 77.03, "stop": 77.265, "duration": 0.23}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "And I take it your answer that he didn't show any withholding (Voice Overlap) with himself.", "start": 77.265, "stop": 82.75, "duration": 5.49}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "His only withholding was apparently with regard to the people that he said had left the party that he knew and knew something about whether or not they were or were not in before.", "start": 82.75, "stop": 95.859, "duration": 13.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "And -- and there was -- and you agree that the record doesn't disclose any -- what shall I say, any indication or explicit endeavor on the part of the Chairman and he was the fellow who was asking question, was he?", "start": 95.859, "stop": 110.734, "duration": 14.88}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 110.734, "stop": 111.763, "duration": 1.03}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "That -- that elucidating why the question, which you refuse to answer, might bail on issues that had been dealt with and as to which he did give testimony?", "start": 111.763, "stop": 124.378, "duration": 12.61}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "I must correct that the questions were asked by the Chairman and various members of the Committee --", "start": 124.378, "stop": 128.633, "duration": 4.26}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "All right.", "start": 128.633, "stop": 129.298, "duration": 0.66}, {"text": "All of them.", "start": 129.298, "stop": 129.872, "duration": 0.57}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "And then --", "start": 129.872, "stop": 131.307, "duration": 1.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "But there was no point at to which -- perhaps I can put it more simply.", "start": 131.307, "stop": 136.192, "duration": 4.89}, {"text": "There was no indication when he said, “No, I don't want to talk about that.”", "start": 136.192, "stop": 139.612, "duration": 3.42}, {"text": "But the Chairman then said, well, may I tell you, politely said incur this evening, maybe employed even before congressional committee to say, may I tell you why I'm asking this for the point of this question or let me enlighten you.", "start": 139.612, "stop": 153.215, "duration": 13.6}, {"text": "There was nothing of that sort, was there?", "start": 153.215, "stop": 155.262, "duration": 2.05}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, except the --", "start": 155.262, "stop": 156.037, "duration": 0.78}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "I mean the question was put and denial made and that's that.", "start": 156.037, "stop": 161.256, "duration": 5.22}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 161.256, "stop": 162.826, "duration": 1.57}, {"text": "There was the one statement by the Chairman, when he direct in -- directed in to answer.", "start": 162.826, "stop": 169.113, "duration": 6.29}, {"text": "In which he said he thought he had information that would be helpful to the Committee and that he should give it.", "start": 169.113, "stop": 175.239, "duration": 6.13}, {"text": "And he then said, he direct him to answer but it doesn't go as broad I think as your question.", "start": 175.239, "stop": 181.857, "duration": 6.62}, {"text": "And it seems to me the only area that the Committee could have said that he was not frank was if he was falsifying about whether he did continue dues to these -- to the Communist Party and through to these very persons, and whether he collected dues from these very persons.", "start": 181.857, "stop": 202.32, "duration": 20.46}, {"text": "And whether he was in fact a Communist when they said he was.", "start": 202.32, "stop": 205.674, "duration": 3.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "And the question that I put to Mr. Rauh, what can you open the door to the extent of saying, I will disclose those whom I know to be members of the Communist Party.", "start": 205.674, "stop": 219.383, "duration": 13.71}, {"text": "The Chairman didn't say, “Well, we do not have to give you of course our information, but there's reason why we ask that in the light of what you already tested.”", "start": 219.383, "stop": 229.35, "duration": 9.97}, {"text": "There's nothing like that?", "start": 229.35, "stop": 230.49, "duration": 1.14}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "No.", "start": 230.49, "stop": 231.42, "duration": 0.93}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "All right.", "start": 231.42, "stop": 232.114, "duration": 0.69}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "There is the record that he knew everything that happened as far as this other inquiry to Spencer and Rumsey.", "start": 232.114, "stop": 240.694, "duration": 8.58}, {"text": "And seems to me much of that shows what the Committee was trying to get at and I'd like to give you a little of that this time.On page 76 of the record, there's a small portion that I'd like to call your attention to over a testimony of Mr. Watkins.", "start": 240.694, "stop": 259.524, "duration": 18.83}, {"text": "Mr. Molder, member of the Committee, then examining was to what extent or in what manner did you cooperate, did you attend meetings of the leadership of the Communist Party, or was your cooperation with some of the movements that they were undertaking in cooperation with the labor at that time?", "start": 259.524, "stop": 275.617, "duration": 16.09}, {"text": "Well, the cooperation as I referred to in my statement was had by contributions.", "start": 275.617, "stop": 281.09, "duration": 5.47}, {"text": "I've been present at meetings, coxes I referred to, and that is what I mean by cooperation.", "start": 281.09, "stop": 287.001, "duration": 5.91}, {"text": "Did you participate in any political meetings where only communist were involved?", "start": 287.001, "stop": 291.349, "duration": 4.35}, {"text": "I have attended in my work in the labor union thousands of meetings, sometimes as many as four days, answered about any specific meeting, it would necessarily have to be pinpointed to some recollection.", "start": 291.349, "stop": 302.704, "duration": 11.36}, {"text": "Well, did you consider yourself as actually affiliating yourself within this cause or the philosophy of the Communist Party movement during that period or time or were you using the Communist Party in your work as a labor leader?", "start": 302.704, "stop": 315.24, "duration": 12.54}, {"text": "That is the point I was trying to make clear a moment ago.", "start": 315.24, "stop": 318.584, "duration": 3.34}, {"text": "I was trying to distinguish.", "start": 318.584, "stop": 320.161, "duration": 1.58}, {"text": "We do distinguish between those activities.", "start": 320.161, "stop": 322.996, "duration": 2.83}, {"text": "Well, I would say that on occasions there was no difference in opinion on a position, which I might have felt the Communist were also in support of that position, and I did not oppose it.", "start": 322.996, "stop": 333.606, "duration": 10.61}, {"text": "But where I felt that their position different with mine, I did oppose.", "start": 333.606, "stop": 337.895, "duration": 4.29}, {"text": "And he goes on and describes in some detail, the collaboration that he had during that period with the members of the Communist Party.", "start": 337.895, "stop": 347.823, "duration": 9.93}, {"text": "Then on page 156 of the record is a detailed testimony of Mr. Spencer, in which each one of these people that the petitioner was later asked about, whether they were members of the Communist Party.", "start": 347.823, "stop": 365.934, "duration": 18.11}, {"text": "Were gone into in detail and the questioning demonstrates, it seems to the Government, very clearly what the Committee was trying to find out.", "start": 365.934, "stop": 375.483, "duration": 9.55}, {"text": "They were asking about the membership of this particular Communist Party sale or group in the quad cities.And then they took each one of them and tried to find out what those people did.", "start": 375.483, "stop": 390.947, "duration": 15.46}, {"text": "Various ones were in the AF of L Union and so we're not in the particular union that the petitioner was in, some of them worked in the city and were not in a union activity, and others were closely identified with the union activity of this particular union that had become infiltrated.", "start": 390.947, "stop": 410.018, "duration": 19.07}, {"text": "In fact, there is one question at the middle of page, what positions in the union were held by members of your branch of the Communist Party?", "start": 410.018, "stop": 419.875, "duration": 9.86}, {"text": "Well, I was vice-chairman of the local and Chairman of the grievance Committee, and Walter Rumsey was Chairman of the local, and Gus Gustafson was secretary of treasurer of the local, and Hazel Jones was the steward in the local, was steward in the tractor drivers.", "start": 419.875, "stop": 434.446, "duration": 14.57}, {"text": "And I believe those are the only executive positions within the local, there were held by many to the Communist Party.", "start": 434.446, "stop": 441.041, "duration": 6.59}, {"text": "Did that virtually assure Communist control of the activities in the union, a good sharer?I would say -- I wouldn't say absolute control, but quite a bit of them.", "start": 441.041, "stop": 452.883, "duration": 11.84}, {"text": "And then they go on with each one these people trying to identify what function they had with relation to union activities in that area, whether they were -- and did find out that they were Communist Party members from Spencer and Rumsey.", "start": 452.883, "stop": 469.536, "duration": 16.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "You mean all?", "start": 469.536, "stop": 470.323, "duration": 0.79}, {"text": "They had already found out that they were, when they asked (Inaudible)", "start": 470.323, "stop": 473.47, "duration": 3.15}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, and he proceeded.", "start": 473.47, "stop": 475.675, "duration": 2.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "What was the purpose in asking him if they already knew?", "start": 475.675, "stop": 478.609, "duration": 2.93}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Was to try to verify the testimony that they had gotten.", "start": 478.609, "stop": 482.257, "duration": 3.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Did they think it was unreliable?", "start": 482.257, "stop": 484.231, "duration": 1.97}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, he had already indicated that was unreliable as to him by saying --", "start": 484.231, "stop": 489.577, "duration": 5.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "But they brought him in.", "start": 489.577, "stop": 491.481, "duration": 1.9}, {"text": "They didn't bring him in to challenge that testimony.", "start": 491.481, "stop": 494.373, "duration": 2.89}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, I don't suppose they anticipated that that would occur.", "start": 494.373, "stop": 498.439, "duration": 4.07}, {"text": "And they were trying to -- maybe it was cumulative, maybe it was more evidence, but it seems to me that that ought to be left to the Committee within any reasonable bounds at all when they were still actively trying to find out the facts about this problem with infiltration --", "start": 498.439, "stop": 517.065, "duration": 18.63}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, Mr. Solicitor, are you suggesting that his denials of their testimony as that testimony related to him --", "start": 517.065, "stop": 525.461, "duration": 8.4}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 525.461, "stop": 526.259, "duration": 0.8}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- may have reflected upon the credibility of their testimony as to these others?", "start": 526.259, "stop": 530.495, "duration": 4.24}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Entirely, yes.", "start": 530.495, "stop": 531.047, "duration": 0.55}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "At least to a degree which justify their pressing the same questions upon him?", "start": 531.047, "stop": 535.777, "duration": 4.73}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, Mr. Justice.", "start": 535.777, "stop": 537.011, "duration": 1.23}, {"text": "It seems to me that in the area of this problem we're dealing with, that the -- the Court should approach it in a hospitable manner to try to give the Congress an opportunity to function within a reasonable limit.", "start": 537.011, "stop": 552.248, "duration": 15.24}, {"text": "And that if this was a court of law and this problem came up, it was reasonable for the Committee to wonder where the truth lies, they had some evidences.", "start": 552.248, "stop": 563.939, "duration": 11.69}, {"text": "In fact, they had evidences in their files, there wasn't any question about that.", "start": 563.939, "stop": 568.146, "duration": 4.21}, {"text": "I don't think that this Court should ever limit the Committee to what's in their file because it might not prove to be the truth at all.", "start": 568.146, "stop": 576.239, "duration": 8.09}, {"text": "And so, upon having such an investigation, part of their -- important part of the very things that you would rely and if you're going to try to act upon such legislation, was the testimony of men like Rumsey and Spencer right here.", "start": 576.239, "stop": 591.946, "duration": 15.71}, {"text": "That this very union had been infiltrated by the Communist Party and that they have gotten all these important officers, if they didn't dominate it, they certainly had an important voice in the control of it.", "start": 591.946, "stop": 603.871, "duration": 11.92}, {"text": "And now this man comes, who maybe is cumulative but still they had a right, it seems to me within the reason to limit to ask him.", "start": 603.871, "stop": 612.108, "duration": 8.24}, {"text": "And they asked him and he says I wasn't a member of the Party --", "start": 612.108, "stop": 615.338, "duration": 3.23}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now, did you suggest before lunch that the legislation bearing expressly upon infiltration in the labor unions followed by only a few months within --", "start": 615.338, "stop": 628.039, "duration": 12.7}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Within -- within four months.", "start": 628.039, "stop": 630.258, "duration": 2.22}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, now, was there was a report of this Committee --", "start": 630.258, "stop": 632.684, "duration": 2.43}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, there was.", "start": 632.684, "stop": 632.749, "duration": 0.07}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- which led to that legislation?", "start": 632.749, "stop": 634.18, "duration": 1.43}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 634.18, "stop": 634.68, "duration": 0.5}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is that on the record?", "start": 634.68, "stop": 635.823, "duration": 1.14}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's referred to in the briefs and counsel for petitioner say, that it doesn't discuss the detail of the testimony.", "start": 635.823, "stop": 648.83, "duration": 13.01}, {"text": "But it does refer expressly, Government states in his brief to the testimony of Rumsey.", "start": 648.83, "stop": 655.991, "duration": 7.16}, {"text": "And that they have had very extended hearings in regard to the whole matter.", "start": 655.991, "stop": 660.444, "duration": 4.45}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "And that was a report in support of the proposed --", "start": 660.444, "stop": 663.166, "duration": 2.72}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "In support of the --", "start": 663.166, "stop": 663.455, "duration": 0.29}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- legislation?", "start": 663.455, "stop": 664.602, "duration": 1.15}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- proposed legislation.", "start": 664.602, "stop": 665.719, "duration": 1.12}, {"text": "Yes.", "start": 665.719, "stop": 666.968, "duration": 1.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "In the Court of Appeals thought that is one of its grounds.", "start": 666.968, "stop": 670.338, "duration": 3.37}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's right.", "start": 670.338, "stop": 671.939, "duration": 1.6}, {"text": "And so, we are saying that in this particular proceeding, that it was a reasonable legislative purpose and legitimate in this, in trying to discover the facts about whether or not to legislate in this matter, to try to find out where the truth lay between these people.", "start": 671.939, "stop": 693.804, "duration": 21.87}, {"text": "Now, we do not claim on behalf of the Government that there's any right to expose for purposes of exposure and I don't know that Congress has ever claimed any such right.", "start": 693.804, "stop": 704.963, "duration": 11.16}, {"text": "But we do say that they're in the same ground, that there is a right to inform the public at the same time they inform the Congress.", "start": 704.963, "stop": 716.307, "duration": 11.34}, {"text": "And I think that's inherent in our system because if matter comes up, then maybe a considerable public opinion in the country that certain legislation should be enacted.", "start": 716.307, "stop": 730.805, "duration": 14.5}, {"text": "And the Congress might make an independent investigation with such skill on investigators that it has and find out, as a matter a fact from that investigation, that legislation is not required, that the situation is not as the public believes it.", "start": 730.805, "stop": 748.942, "duration": 18.14}, {"text": "Now, it seems to me it's very proper for them to have a hearing and develop the facts.", "start": 748.942, "stop": 754.148, "duration": 5.21}, {"text": "Not only to show to Congress, that there is no need for legislation in that area, but also to show the public, because under a democratic system, the legislation responds to public opinion and demand.", "start": 754.148, "stop": 769.786, "duration": 15.64}, {"text": "And so as long as that's related in that manner, it seems to me that's legitimate and that this Court should not prevent the Congress from carrying on that kind of an activity.", "start": 769.786, "stop": 782.656, "duration": 12.87}, {"text": "It is merely to expose for exposure's sake, we do not claim any such thing and we don't believe that the Congress does.", "start": 782.656, "stop": 794.164, "duration": 11.51}, {"text": "I think there's another important problem --", "start": 794.164, "stop": 796.144, "duration": 1.98}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "You mean by that, that you do not think that the resolution, under which the Committee was acting, would authorize attempting to expose for exposure's sake?", "start": 796.144, "stop": 807.65, "duration": 11.51}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, I did -- I think two things.", "start": 807.65, "stop": 810.053, "duration": 2.4}, {"text": "That's true that it did not, and secondly, I do not think that this -- the facts of this hearing shows there was any purpose to do anything of that kind.", "start": 810.053, "stop": 819.889, "duration": 9.84}, {"text": "I think that this Committee was diligently trying to find out facts upon which they could legislate and did legislate within a very short period of time.", "start": 819.889, "stop": 831.579, "duration": 11.69}, {"text": "It's next suggested that in trying to determine whether this action or hearing was a -- and the questions under it, were a proper -- had a proper legislative purpose, that the Court must not confine itself to the resolution of the Congress, which counsels developed.", "start": 831.579, "stop": 860.684, "duration": 29.11}, {"text": "And the hearing itself but must turn to extraneous evidence of all unsoundly kinds.", "start": 860.684, "stop": 869.18, "duration": 8.5}, {"text": "I think that is a situation that's impossible for the courts to be asked to deal with.", "start": 869.18, "stop": 875.679, "duration": 6.5}, {"text": "It's unreasonable and I'd like to develop just briefly the problems that would result from it.", "start": 875.679, "stop": 882.551, "duration": 6.87}, {"text": "It's the Governments position -- I'd like to make it clear that the Court should confine itself to the resolution of the Congress and the hearing proceedings of whatever happened in the hearing.", "start": 882.551, "stop": 897.931, "duration": 15.38}, {"text": "Now, if you go beyond that, you have the question of whether or not you're going to try the members of the Congress.", "start": 897.931, "stop": 906.806, "duration": 8.88}, {"text": "Are you going to inquire of each Committee member as to what his position is with regard to a particular matter?", "start": 906.806, "stop": 915.615, "duration": 8.81}, {"text": "What his motives were in making certain inquires to a certain witness?", "start": 915.615, "stop": 923.547, "duration": 7.93}, {"text": "Are you going to rely on that or do you have to go from the Subcommittee to the whole Committee?", "start": 923.547, "stop": 930.438, "duration": 6.89}, {"text": "Or do you have to go beyond that, from the House and include the Senate, because each of them engaged in this activity.", "start": 930.438, "stop": 942.385, "duration": 11.95}, {"text": "It seems to me it's an impossible situation to do that.", "start": 942.385, "stop": 945.549, "duration": 3.16}, {"text": "If the Chairman makes a speech or statement in which he purports to state what the purpose of intention is.", "start": 945.549, "stop": 956.333, "duration": 10.78}, {"text": "I don't see how the Congress itself should be bound by anything of that character, unless it is brought to the attention of the Congress in such a way and the Congress takes a vote or some action that this Court would feel it would have to respect this congressional action.", "start": 956.333, "stop": 973.784, "duration": 17.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "That -- that may bear -- that may be relevant.", "start": 973.784, "stop": 977.446, "duration": 3.66}, {"text": "I can see how it is relevant as to validity of the resolution itself.", "start": 977.446, "stop": 987.009, "duration": 9.56}, {"text": "But the other take care of the specific question of propriety the enforced questioning of specific question.", "start": 987.009, "stop": 997.895, "duration": 10.89}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, the problem it seems to me is that if you are going to inquire as to this particular Committee, then they put in the record here which the court below not receive all kinds of statements by Mr. Velde, speeches, quotations from the various newspapers and statements by others in -- who would acted in connection with such a Committee.", "start": 997.895, "stop": 1025.25, "duration": 27.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "I understood that some of the statements were made in the course of --", "start": 1025.25, "stop": 1028.598, "duration": 3.35}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Hearing.", "start": 1028.598, "stop": 1028.8, "duration": 0.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- the activity of the Committee itself, hearing.", "start": 1028.8, "stop": 1031.092, "duration": 2.29}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's right.", "start": 1031.092, "stop": 1031.567, "duration": 0.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "As to that, I don't suppose you have to make all for approve.", "start": 1031.567, "stop": 1034.361, "duration": 2.79}, {"text": "I should think that is really judicial notice, isn't it?", "start": 1034.361, "stop": 1038.671, "duration": 4.31}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, of course, if it was a part of this proceeding, even as started in and for the whole period of time, which we consider a continuous proceeding.", "start": 1038.671, "stop": 1048.872, "duration": 10.2}, {"text": "It would certainly be proper for the Court to examine that and find out what was doing (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 1048.872, "stop": 1053.068, "duration": 4.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Not as evidence but --", "start": 1053.068, "stop": 1054.8, "duration": 1.73}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "As it's bearing upon (Voice Overlap).", "start": 1054.8, "stop": 1056.511, "duration": 1.71}, {"text": "That's right.", "start": 1056.511, "stop": 1057.725, "duration": 1.21}, {"text": "But these are statements that go back of that to other times when the Committee was acting and its membership changed over the years.", "start": 1057.725, "stop": 1067.099, "duration": 9.37}, {"text": "Its chairmanship changed, and how a Committee at this particular time can be bound by all of the different things that someone might say outside of the hearings or even in the hearings that were not a part of this particular Committee's activity for the period.", "start": 1067.099, "stop": 1085.442, "duration": 18.34}, {"text": "That it was constituted as not under the Congress.", "start": 1085.442, "stop": 1088.985, "duration": 3.54}, {"text": "It seems to present problems that are almost impossible of solution if the courts get into that.", "start": 1088.985, "stop": 1095.616, "duration": 6.63}, {"text": "And we feel that the only way that you can fairly treat the Congress in the consideration of this problem is to deal with the places where it took action.", "start": 1095.616, "stop": 1107.463, "duration": 11.85}, {"text": "And all of the proceedings, of the hearings certainly ought to be examined to see whether it was a valid approach to try and carry out the congressional function and the resolution that empowered them to act.", "start": 1107.463, "stop": 1119.375, "duration": 11.91}, {"text": "And the other things you've read to see some member of the Committee might speak up and express some idea that none of the other members would be willing to accept but wouldn't want to because of the situation to take -- to cause any offense by taking acceptance -- exception to it at that moment.", "start": 1119.375, "stop": 1141.608, "duration": 22.23}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Are you going to mention the relationship of these questions to the investigation of propaganda?", "start": 1141.608, "stop": 1149.764, "duration": 8.16}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1149.764, "stop": 1152.522, "duration": 2.76}, {"text": "The --", "start": 1152.522, "stop": 1153.259, "duration": 0.74}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "As I recall it, Mr. Solicitor General, I just look it to see.", "start": 1153.259, "stop": 1158.076, "duration": 4.82}, {"text": "The Court relies pretty extensively on statements outside the Committee hearings in the case of United States against Lovett to find out what was the purpose of the Congress and the Committee in passing the bill.", "start": 1158.076, "stop": 1174.262, "duration": 16.19}, {"text": "Yoy -- you say they could not do it here?", "start": 1174.262, "stop": 1177.137, "duration": 2.88}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I think that we would be getting into an area that would be almost impossible to resolve anything from.", "start": 1177.137, "stop": 1183.621, "duration": 6.48}, {"text": "And that the Court should, like the lower court did, confine itself to the resolution and the proceedings.", "start": 1183.621, "stop": 1191.687, "duration": 8.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "And not refer the reports or speeches made by Congressman Velde in the House on the subject.", "start": 1191.687, "stop": 1201.273, "duration": 9.59}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, I -- I think that those reports are referred to here and there's no question about those.", "start": 1201.273, "stop": 1209.877, "duration": 8.6}, {"text": "But as to speeches on the outside, I don't think those are binding upon the Congress.", "start": 1209.877, "stop": 1213.411, "duration": 3.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "What about from the inside?", "start": 1213.411, "stop": 1215.135, "duration": 1.72}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "I beg your pardon?", "start": 1215.135, "stop": 1215.868, "duration": 0.73}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "What about inside?", "start": 1215.868, "stop": 1217.068, "duration": 1.2}, {"text": "I -- I understood him to say some of them made inside the Congress.", "start": 1217.068, "stop": 1220.627, "duration": 3.56}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, if they were in connection with legislation, I think it would have bearing on the legislation but not in connection as to these particular hearings and whether or not there was a valid legislative purpose as to the questions at hand.", "start": 1220.627, "stop": 1239.123, "duration": 18.5}, {"text": "Now, I dealt with -- and call Court's particular attention to the several references in the inquiry to Mr. Rumsey on pages 138 and 139, directly to the question of propaganda, that were being asked him in connection with his examination.", "start": 1239.123, "stop": 1268.725, "duration": 29.6}, {"text": "And as the position of the Government, that this was a part of the hearings that was continuous, that they brought to the attention of this petitioner the fact that he was fairly familiar with the examination of Mr. Rumsey.", "start": 1268.725, "stop": 1288.416, "duration": 19.69}, {"text": "And it was contemplated that the same area would be examined in connection with Mr. Watkins.", "start": 1288.416, "stop": 1296.727, "duration": 8.31}, {"text": "And that the examination never proceeded to that point, because they got to a place where the witness was unwilling to answer questions which they thought had an important bearing upon his credibility and didn't see any purpose in trying to go further to cover any greater area with him.", "start": 1296.727, "stop": 1320.65, "duration": 23.92}]}, {"speakerName": "William O. Douglas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Did they ask him any question about his activities, the relation to propaganda?", "start": 1320.65, "stop": 1327.525, "duration": 6.88}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Only what I read to you --", "start": 1327.525, "stop": 1330.088, "duration": 2.56}]}, {"speakerName": "William O. Douglas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Not Rumsey, I mean Watkins.", "start": 1330.088, "stop": 1331.796, "duration": 1.71}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1331.796, "stop": 1332.312, "duration": 0.52}, {"text": "On page 76, they asked him in regard to his various activities and he told about his participation in various types of activities that involved petitions that he signed, the things of that kind were certainly part of the propaganda of the Communist Party, as generally understood.", "start": 1332.312, "stop": 1355.195, "duration": 22.88}, {"text": "And they also inquired about his activities in regard to the purposes and plans of the Party that he supported and accepted.", "start": 1355.195, "stop": 1366.253, "duration": 11.06}, {"text": "And the parts that he rejected when it didn't go along with his ideas of what was the thing to do with the union.", "start": 1366.253, "stop": 1374.964, "duration": 8.71}, {"text": "So that they were covering the general area all the time, not only with him but the other witnesses of the propaganda and all of the activities that are connected with the Communist Party.", "start": 1374.964, "stop": 1393.689, "duration": 18.73}, {"text": "The position of the Government that the Communist Party is involved in a propaganda movement, that's inherent, and it is also involved in action in trying to get that ideology accepted and applied in so many places that it can.", "start": 1393.689, "stop": 1418.322, "duration": 24.63}, {"text": "That is inherent and as then so recognized that this -- over the years that such inquiries basic as to any inquiry about the activities of the Communist Party.", "start": 1418.322, "stop": 1432.865, "duration": 14.54}, {"text": "And here, they were trying to see what those activities were.", "start": 1432.865, "stop": 1437.228, "duration": 4.36}, {"text": "What the petitions in the various solicitation and efforts to recruit members had accomplished, whether they had actually gotten control of this union or how much control they had gotten, and what the effect of it was.", "start": 1437.228, "stop": 1452.804, "duration": 15.58}, {"text": "I think it was a reasonable inquiry to follow that up and find out why these people had left the Communist Party, if they had.", "start": 1452.804, "stop": 1461.626, "duration": 8.82}, {"text": "As the witness seemed to indicate, they had derived at a -- sometime, when they had decided to leave that Party, it was not indicated when and if so, why?", "start": 1461.626, "stop": 1473.214, "duration": 11.59}, {"text": "Because that would have a bearing upon, whether to -- there was a need for the legislation and -- or whether the need has disappeared.", "start": 1473.214, "stop": 1483.18, "duration": 9.97}, {"text": "And the whole question of it was before the Congress and before the Committee at the time.", "start": 1483.18, "stop": 1495.929, "duration": 12.75}, {"text": "The Government contends that there was no limitation upon the activity of the Committee and should not be any limitation, because it had some information in its files.", "start": 1495.929, "stop": 1508.325, "duration": 12.4}, {"text": "It seems to us that this case is a very clear demonstration of the reason why there should be no such limitation.", "start": 1508.325, "stop": 1517.839, "duration": 9.51}, {"text": "It's argued that since the Committee already had some of this information, much of it in its files, that therefore there is no basis for having a valid legislative purpose in making further inquiry.", "start": 1517.839, "stop": 1537.533, "duration": 19.69}, {"text": "First place, this -- this examination showed that there was a difference between what it had in its files and there's some argument by petitioner that the counsel for the Committee was not thoroughly aware of what was in the files.", "start": 1537.533, "stop": 1557.193, "duration": 19.66}, {"text": "It was shown that there was a considerable mass of evidence that the Committee did have in these files.", "start": 1557.193, "stop": 1564.007, "duration": 6.81}, {"text": "But the counsel did testify that he was briefed carefully in regard to this particular matter and whatever the Committee had by the investigators who were supposed to be familiar with the material and the files, and he then proceeded to make the various inquiry.", "start": 1564.007, "stop": 1602.703, "duration": 38.7}, {"text": "The Government takes the position that the question of Communist Party membership is a proper inquiry for any legislative committee dealing in subject matter that is involved in that of the -- under the resolution of the Un-American Activities Committee.", "start": 1602.703, "stop": 1623.782, "duration": 21.08}, {"text": "And this Court has passed upon whether or not that's a proper type of legislation, sufficient numbers of times in Douds and other cases, so that there could be no question but what that inquiries is proper.", "start": 1623.782, "stop": 1637.484, "duration": 13.7}, {"text": "It seems to us in this case, there is even a greater reason for such an inquiry in view of the conflict between the witnesses concerning Mr. Watkins' membership in the Party.", "start": 1637.484, "stop": 1652.141, "duration": 14.66}, {"text": "And whether these other people were (Inaudible) activities and so forth.", "start": 1652.141, "stop": 1681.293, "duration": 29.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Solicitor, if this kind of a question had been asked in adversary preceding in Court and the witness is asked if you know so and so.", "start": 1681.293, "stop": 1698.779, "duration": 17.49}, {"text": "And he said, I don't want to answer that.", "start": 1698.779, "stop": 1702.642, "duration": 3.86}, {"text": "And nothing more appears in here as to relevancy, the argument you have made.", "start": 1702.642, "stop": 1716.539, "duration": 13.9}, {"text": "Would you -- and the theory of asking, do you know John Smith?", "start": 1716.539, "stop": 1722.217, "duration": 5.68}, {"text": "But if he said yes and if he says no, it's blocked unless you go and disprove the -- his denial.", "start": 1722.217, "stop": 1729.004, "duration": 6.79}, {"text": "But if he said -- the theory of asking that question is because it leads to some other questions.", "start": 1729.004, "stop": 1733.191, "duration": 4.19}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1733.191, "stop": 1735.446, "duration": 2.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Of course counsel say what I -- the witness says this is -- this will have a tendency to make my client to do something that is disagreeable or to be an informer etcetera.", "start": 1735.446, "stop": 1748.396, "duration": 12.95}, {"text": "Wouldn't -- wouldn't the presiding judge say, what's the point of this question?", "start": 1748.396, "stop": 1758.317, "duration": 9.92}, {"text": "What are you trying -- what subject matter do you seek to elicit from this witness?", "start": 1758.317, "stop": 1763.73, "duration": 5.41}, {"text": "Wouldn't counsel be asked to give some indication why that question should be answered as a preliminary to some other question?", "start": 1763.73, "stop": 1772.099, "duration": 8.37}, {"text": "And the relation in the chain of relevant sequence of such an opening question?", "start": 1772.099, "stop": 1777.856, "duration": 5.76}, {"text": "Where the counsel say, well, I stand on that question, I want that.", "start": 1777.856, "stop": 1781.71, "duration": 3.85}, {"text": "And the Court rules there have denied them.", "start": 1781.71, "stop": 1785.371, "duration": 3.66}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think --", "start": 1785.371, "stop": 1785.97, "duration": 0.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Am I -- am I wrong in thinking that nobody would dream of reversing that denial, say that the judge couldn't have said no?", "start": 1785.97, "stop": 1794.587, "duration": 8.62}, {"text": "Let the witness stand on that refusal?", "start": 1794.587, "stop": 1797.122, "duration": 2.54}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think it would depend on what the record was up to that point.", "start": 1797.122, "stop": 1801.01, "duration": 3.89}, {"text": "And if it looked at those inquiries have been made, we assume that the witness knew what that record was and that inquiries have been made like this had been in regard to activity in this union and --", "start": 1801.01, "stop": 1815.575, "duration": 14.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, the most he could get out of them is that he would say, yes, I knew him.", "start": 1815.575, "stop": 1818.619, "duration": 3.04}, {"text": "Was he a communist?", "start": 1818.619, "stop": 1819.516, "duration": 0.9}, {"text": "Yes, he was at the time.", "start": 1819.516, "stop": 1821.101, "duration": 1.59}, {"text": "Could he get any more out of them than that?", "start": 1821.101, "stop": 1822.882, "duration": 1.78}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I think if you -- he could also get out, whether he left the Party if he puts the witness that indicated that that was the reason.", "start": 1822.882, "stop": 1832.051, "duration": 9.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Then he'll ask Watkins.", "start": 1832.051, "stop": 1833.37, "duration": 1.32}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, I mean, the various persons that were inquired about.", "start": 1833.37, "stop": 1837.905, "duration": 4.54}, {"text": "The witness had refused to testify about because --", "start": 1837.905, "stop": 1840.651, "duration": 2.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "You mean some other -- and not the witness in question, not Watkins?", "start": 1840.651, "stop": 1844.353, "duration": 3.7}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Watkins said that the reason he would not testify about them was because they had -- they were known to him --", "start": 1844.353, "stop": 1851.016, "duration": 6.66}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Because he (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 1851.016, "stop": 1851.57, "duration": 0.55}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- not to be (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 1851.57, "stop": 1852.516, "duration": 0.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- to be -- not known to be a Communist.", "start": 1852.516, "stop": 1854.29, "duration": 1.77}, {"text": "Very well.", "start": 1854.29, "stop": 1854.428, "duration": 0.14}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1854.428, "stop": 1855.338, "duration": 0.91}, {"text": "And so you could also ask, not only whether there was membership, but whether or not they had left the Party at sometime --", "start": 1855.338, "stop": 1863.848, "duration": 8.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "That would be a dubious source of information as to where another person did, I should think.", "start": 1863.848, "stop": 1869.256, "duration": 5.41}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well --", "start": 1869.256, "stop": 1869.524, "duration": 0.27}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm not -- everything you connected with everything else in this world.", "start": 1869.524, "stop": 1872.002, "duration": 2.48}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1872.002, "stop": 1872.406, "duration": 0.4}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, eventually.", "start": 1872.406, "stop": 1874.155, "duration": 1.75}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, they --", "start": 1874.155, "stop": 1874.648, "duration": 0.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Isn't it rather 10 years to be connected, to ask Watkins to find out why a lot of other people left or whether they have left?", "start": 1874.648, "stop": 1881.684, "duration": 7.04}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, the testimony was that he was a part of this very same Communist group in this area but they were all members of it.", "start": 1881.684, "stop": 1890.912, "duration": 9.23}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, he -- was there any testimony that he was the secretary of -- that he was (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 1890.912, "stop": 1894.626, "duration": 3.71}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That they attended the meetings.", "start": 1894.626, "stop": 1896.08, "duration": 1.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Pardon me?", "start": 1896.08, "stop": 1896.453, "duration": 0.37}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "There was testimony that he attended the meetings.", "start": 1896.453, "stop": 1898.532, "duration": 2.08}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, but --", "start": 1898.532, "stop": 1899.564, "duration": 1.03}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Over the years.", "start": 1899.564, "stop": 1901.509, "duration": 1.94}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Out of that, you get him as a good source of information or a reliable source of information of a lot of other people did, that seem to me a little remote to the subject matter.", "start": 1901.509, "stop": 1912.331, "duration": 10.82}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, they had obtained such information from Rumsey and Spencer, and they were -- he had questioned the fact that he was a member and they were then trying to find out whether he verified or denied.", "start": 1912.331, "stop": 1927.024, "duration": 14.69}, {"text": "And they didn't indicate that they were trying to find one answer or the other from him.", "start": 1927.024, "stop": 1931.61, "duration": 4.59}, {"text": "And I -- it appeared the Committee was in good faith trying to find out what the fact was.", "start": 1931.61, "stop": 1936.698, "duration": 5.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm assuming that and I'm assuming you would have given a favorable answer, favorable to their point of view and I don't see how -- I fail to see that how much or to what extent, to what serious extent, that would advance their purposes.", "start": 1936.698, "stop": 1953.463, "duration": 16.76}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, it would held a serious effect on whether or not there was a verification of what Rumsey and Spencer had already testified to, as to the question of infiltration.", "start": 1953.463, "stop": 1967.022, "duration": 13.56}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I didn't suppose that was under denial.", "start": 1967.022, "stop": 1970.275, "duration": 3.25}, {"text": "I mean one could almost take that --", "start": 1970.275, "stop": 1973.64, "duration": 3.37}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Presume that --", "start": 1973.64, "stop": 1974.213, "duration": 0.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- unduly, I could almost take judicial notice of the fact there's a good deal of infiltration in various unions.", "start": 1974.213, "stop": 1979.527, "duration": 5.31}, {"text": "And that wasn't in controversy as between Watkins and the Committee, was it?", "start": 1979.527, "stop": 1984.199, "duration": 4.67}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, as what they were going into, but the fact that Watkins denied his own participation certainly raised the question of whether these people are wrong about all the others and made the inquiry reasonable to reach out and see if they could --", "start": 1984.199, "stop": 2002.062, "duration": 17.86}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "That if his testimony might have exculpated all those, about whom they were pretty confident they were Communist.", "start": 2002.062, "stop": 2007.632, "duration": 5.57}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's right or at least show that there were in error in relying on any such evidence as that in connection with their recommendation to the Congress.", "start": 2007.632, "stop": 2019.154, "duration": 11.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "What was his job?", "start": 2019.154, "stop": 2020.914, "duration": 1.76}, {"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 2020.914, "stop": 2022.287, "duration": 1.37}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, he was a vice-president of the union and of the Farm Equipment Union.", "start": 2022.287, "stop": 2031.471, "duration": 9.18}, {"text": "And it was that union that anticipated him and was infiltrated, an inquiry was involved.", "start": 2031.471, "stop": 2039.504, "duration": 8.03}, {"text": "And then the persons that were described in the testimony that I read to you were also persons who became members of the Communist Party and so it was considered considerable control if not dominance of the --", "start": 2039.504, "stop": 2056.273, "duration": 16.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "They were all in this union?", "start": 2056.273, "stop": 2057.98, "duration": 1.71}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "I beg your pardon?", "start": 2057.98, "stop": 2058.599, "duration": 0.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "They were all in the same union when he was vice-president?", "start": 2058.599, "stop": 2061.775, "duration": 3.18}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "No.", "start": 2061.775, "stop": 2062.242, "duration": 0.47}, {"text": "Not -- not all the people that were asked about.", "start": 2062.242, "stop": 2064.748, "duration": 2.51}, {"text": "The same -- the people that I described that were officers were in the same union.", "start": 2064.748, "stop": 2070.69, "duration": 5.94}, {"text": "But in the Committee's inquiry, in regard to all of these long list of other people, it was shown that some of them were members of other unions.", "start": 2070.69, "stop": 2082.21, "duration": 11.52}, {"text": "Some of them were active in city life and were not in union activity at all.", "start": 2082.21, "stop": 2088.791, "duration": 6.58}, {"text": "And others were a part of this union activity and actively forwarding the Communist cause in this union.", "start": 2088.791, "stop": 2096.629, "duration": 7.84}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Did the Committee report this incident to the Congress?", "start": 2096.629, "stop": 2100.715, "duration": 4.09}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Not the detail of it.", "start": 2100.715, "stop": 2102.057, "duration": 1.34}, {"text": "It was reported before the action in regard to the contempt.", "start": 2102.057, "stop": 2108.043, "duration": 5.99}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "When they reported it to the Congress, did they give any indication as to the relevancy of the evidence?", "start": 2108.043, "stop": 2117.055, "duration": 9.01}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Not any -- not in any detail.", "start": 2117.055, "stop": 2119.213, "duration": 2.16}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "How did they -- did the Congress just vote on it when there's -- without any report or any indication of any kind as to the materiality of it?", "start": 2119.213, "stop": 2127.916, "duration": 8.7}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "They reported the fact of the inquiries that were made and the failure to answer, and asked that the action be reported by the speaker -- sent by the speaker to the United States Attorney for action.", "start": 2127.916, "stop": 2145.338, "duration": 17.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Was that all that took place?", "start": 2145.338, "stop": 2147.197, "duration": 1.86}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, they also had the report of the Committee in regard to this legislation which described here, the investigations in general terms.", "start": 2147.197, "stop": 2157.895, "duration": 10.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "But there was no discussion and no -- of the report that they made asking if he be cited, or any explanation as to the relevancy or irrelevancy of the evidence?", "start": 2157.895, "stop": 2170.541, "duration": 12.65}, {"text": "No question?", "start": 2170.541, "stop": 2171.462, "duration": 0.92}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "No.", "start": 2171.462, "stop": 2172.158, "duration": 0.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is that the normal way and is that the conventional way in which the Committee that is bulked in its inquiry, reports to the House or Senate respectively and ask that the matter be referred to the Department of Justice or U.S. Attorney, whatever it is?", "start": 2172.158, "stop": 2187.12, "duration": 14.96}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's my understanding as to usual way, I would -- I am not inquiring into that, I would have to check it (Inaudible) --", "start": 2187.12, "stop": 2194.73, "duration": 7.61}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Would you be good enough to do it?", "start": 2194.73, "stop": 2195.778, "duration": 1.05}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'll do that.", "start": 2195.778, "stop": 2196.695, "duration": 0.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Go back to some distant when you do, so that we won't just get what happened right recently.", "start": 2196.695, "stop": 2202.226, "duration": 5.53}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, I will.", "start": 2202.226, "stop": 2203.357, "duration": 1.13}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Solicitor, assuming a legislative purpose in this question, what have you to say to Mr. Rauh's point that nevertheless the First Amendment stood as a bar against they're being put to Watkins?", "start": 2203.357, "stop": 2217, "duration": 13.64}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "It seems to the Government that that claim of the First Amendment, in the first place it was not made until in this Court and I think in the Court of Appeals it was also made, but it was not made at the time of the hearing.", "start": 2217, "stop": 2236.207, "duration": 19.21}, {"text": "Secondly, we feel that --", "start": 2236.207, "stop": 2239.397, "duration": 3.19}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Which hearing?", "start": 2239.397, "stop": 2239.894, "duration": 0.5}, {"text": "Do you mean the -- before the Committee?", "start": 2239.894, "stop": 2241.143, "duration": 1.25}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Before the Committee.", "start": 2241.143, "stop": 2243.153, "duration": 2.01}, {"text": "That the claim of the First Amendment is being made not on behalf of this petitioner, but on behalf of these other people.", "start": 2243.153, "stop": 2254.457, "duration": 11.3}, {"text": "And that the constitutional right is a personal right.", "start": 2254.457, "stop": 2259.197, "duration": 4.74}, {"text": "It belongs to these other people and there's no right in the petitioner to say, \"I don't want to tell anything about John Jones because --", "start": 2259.197, "stop": 2269.165, "duration": 9.97}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I thought Mr. Rauh's point was -- I maybe wrong that the right arising from the First Amendment is that the witness be saved the humiliation of being what at least to him, is the invidious position of being an informer.", "start": 2269.165, "stop": 2285.409, "duration": 16.24}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, assuming that there -- if that is the position, we don't think that there is a right of silence in connection with the First Amendment.", "start": 2285.409, "stop": 2296.374, "duration": 10.96}, {"text": "That the protection of the First Amendment is for the right of speech and the opportunity to speak so that the various positions or ideas maybe presented and considered, and even cause a change, lawfully in the form of Government.", "start": 2296.374, "stop": 2320.888, "duration": 24.51}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "In other words, it covers what maybe emitted and that's what maybe remained undisclosed?", "start": 2320.888, "stop": 2331.096, "duration": 10.21}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, Mr. Justice.", "start": 2331.096, "stop": 2331.613, "duration": 0.52}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is that it?", "start": 2331.613, "stop": 2332.71, "duration": 1.1}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "However, there's -- if there is any right of that character, it seems to us that the -- that must be balanced against the right of the Congress to carry out its constitutional power as a legislative body.", "start": 2332.71, "stop": 2348.824, "duration": 16.11}, {"text": "And that in this situation, that the legislative purpose is valid if they were trying to develop that and develop the information so Congress would have the knowledge that the right to inquire must be as broad as the right to legislate in order that Congress have the information that it can make valid desirable legislation pass it.", "start": 2348.824, "stop": 2374.655, "duration": 25.83}, {"text": "And that in balancing those rights which of course are not absolute that the congressional need must be recognized and it would be the one that would prevail in this situation and have to if we're going to have the Congress -- have the information that it must have for legislation.", "start": 2374.655, "stop": 2395.958, "duration": 21.3}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "That suggest then that only the Fifth Amendment is their protection against a refusal to speak if there is a connection legislatively of the question.", "start": 2395.958, "stop": 2405.46, "duration": 9.5}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's right.", "start": 2405.46, "stop": 2407.179, "duration": 1.72}, {"text": "There is a question of pertinency of course under the statute.", "start": 2407.179, "stop": 2409.283, "duration": 2.1}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I'm assuming for legislative purposes.", "start": 2409.283, "stop": 2410.346, "duration": 1.06}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, that's what I thought was the question.", "start": 2410.346, "stop": 2412.506, "duration": 2.16}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "And if there's a balance in the process, I suppose it wouldn't be in the abstract, I don't know where there is but you would look in a particular instance to see if it invaded the right of the First Amendment to any extent?", "start": 2412.506, "stop": 2428.062, "duration": 15.56}, {"text": "I'm quoted it was in that particular case as to have but the -- took get this information and balance it against the right to be silent if there was one?", "start": 2428.062, "stop": 2443.138, "duration": 15.08}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well --", "start": 2443.138, "stop": 2443.437, "duration": 0.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "You couldn't do it in the abstract could you?", "start": 2443.437, "stop": 2445.343, "duration": 1.91}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "No.", "start": 2445.343, "stop": 2445.572, "duration": 0.23}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "If you're going to have a balancing process.", "start": 2445.572, "stop": 2447.397, "duration": 1.82}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "I -- I agree you couldn't do it in the abstract, Mr. Justice Black, but I do think that the power that you're dealing with here is with regard to a coequal branch of the Government.", "start": 2447.397, "stop": 2462.523, "duration": 15.13}, {"text": "And I think that just as you are very careful about declaring any congressional action to be unconstitutional when they legislate that even more so in this area, the Congress needs to have a recognition of the fact that it has to have knowledge, that it has to have information.", "start": 2462.523, "stop": 2488.556, "duration": 26.03}, {"text": "And here, you're dealing not with a particular law but with the power to conduct legislation -- legislative activity itself, and therefore, all of those considerations have to be taken into account when you're making the decision.", "start": 2488.556, "stop": 2505.766, "duration": 17.21}, {"text": "And the presumption if you are dealing with the activity of another court, lower court, would be that it would be a valid action, that the court was -- taken.", "start": 2505.766, "stop": 2518.281, "duration": 12.51}, {"text": "And it seems to be it should be a fortiori as to the Congress in a particular -- in a situation, so that -- and I do not think that you can disregard properly the rules that should apply to examine into this area of congressional action, and its -- and the needs of the Congress to be able to inquire and that there should be a presumption that when an inquiry is being made, that they are trying to do it in accordance with their duties and responsibilities.", "start": 2518.281, "stop": 2554.698, "duration": 36.42}, {"text": "And that you take along all of that laws in applying the -- or answering the question about your situation as we have here.", "start": 2554.698, "stop": 2566.58, "duration": 11.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "This was a Subcommittee, was this not?", "start": 2566.58, "stop": 2568.608, "duration": 2.03}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 2568.608, "stop": 2569.398, "duration": 0.79}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "How many members on this?", "start": 2569.398, "stop": 2570.916, "duration": 1.52}, {"text": "Was there three or five?", "start": 2570.916, "stop": 2573.954, "duration": 3.04}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "My recollection is that they're not required to be --", "start": 2573.954, "stop": 2578.816, "duration": 4.86}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "In this -- in the actual -- in the actual inquiry, how many?", "start": 2578.816, "stop": 2582.97, "duration": 4.15}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "I -- I'll have to check that.", "start": 2582.97, "stop": 2584.175, "duration": 1.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "But it was a Subcommittee?", "start": 2584.175, "stop": 2585.031, "duration": 0.86}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, it was.", "start": 2585.031, "stop": 2587.904, "duration": 2.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Let me ask you this, Mr. Solicitor, and the question I'm going to ask you in one who I think is conscious of the -- in grave questions raised by this, more particularly who were -- does not think that we ought to be (Inaudible) here, confining in this power of Congress, scrutinize independently whether it's -- what the -- whether its legislation maybe potentially relevant or not.", "start": 2587.904, "stop": 2616.319, "duration": 28.41}, {"text": "It's from that point of view that I ask.", "start": 2616.319, "stop": 2619.738, "duration": 3.42}, {"text": "How restrictive of everything, how embarrassing to the plea that you're making and from my point of view properly making?", "start": 2619.738, "stop": 2627.844, "duration": 8.11}, {"text": "And I'd say it carries to through the case, I have any opinion on.", "start": 2627.844, "stop": 2632.231, "duration": 4.39}, {"text": "But from the point of view with -- to which you're addressing yourself, namely, the importance of the coordinate branch of the Government and the duty to get enlightenment before you legislate or to get enlightenment in order to decide not to legislate.", "start": 2632.231, "stop": 2646.888, "duration": 14.66}, {"text": "How curving, how trampling to a generous view of that would it be to say that when a -- when a witness before a committee refuses to answer or states a ground withholding that certainly on the phase of it, is an honorable refusal, certainly on the phase of it is one to which one responds as the -- in the ordinary civilized society.", "start": 2646.888, "stop": 2676.533, "duration": 29.64}, {"text": "How crippling would it be to all to the most generous and hospitable alliance of the congressional power of inquiry to say that when you have no more than this, it all events you ought to be fortified in the relevance by saying, \"Well, we'll adjourn.", "start": 2676.533, "stop": 2694.907, "duration": 18.37}, {"text": "We'll get a vote of the full committee.\"", "start": 2694.907, "stop": 2696.628, "duration": 1.72}, {"text": "Or \"we'll make it clear by explicitness that this does bear on the legislative purpose.\"", "start": 2696.628, "stop": 2702.823, "duration": 6.19}, {"text": "And my legislative purpose that I have indicated means not only that they must legislate but they often -- ought not to legislate.", "start": 2702.823, "stop": 2710.386, "duration": 7.56}, {"text": "How much -- how curving would it be not to let it dried off on this -- ask a question, you know John Smith?", "start": 2710.386, "stop": 2717.269, "duration": 6.88}, {"text": "You know William Jones?", "start": 2717.269, "stop": 2718.181, "duration": 0.91}, {"text": "You know Henry Robinson?", "start": 2718.181, "stop": 2720.691, "duration": 2.51}, {"text": "And you know Fred Phillips?", "start": 2720.691, "stop": 2723.013, "duration": 2.32}, {"text": "And then come down with a contempt power not exercised by Congress on its own responsibility but going to the courts and asking the courts to impose that criminal sanction?", "start": 2723.013, "stop": 2735.973, "duration": 12.96}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh, I -- I think that the -- I mean the facts of this particular situation, that the assumption of the Congress trying to act fair and in partially, they're entitled to and to have that applied in this particular case.", "start": 2735.973, "stop": 2758.148, "duration": 22.18}, {"text": "Now, if you assume that they were not acting -- trying to act fairly --", "start": 2758.148, "stop": 2763.367, "duration": 5.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm not assuming anything.", "start": 2763.367, "stop": 2764.447, "duration": 1.08}, {"text": "I'm just assuming that what you rightly put to the Court in their balancing, that when you extract testimony from a witness, who gives the reason as this man did to himself has not been invasive as to anything pertaining to his own conduct.", "start": 2764.447, "stop": 2781.777, "duration": 17.33}, {"text": "He's ready to be pillared to the extent of that pillar he's in and then says you're asking me now about people who -- who seem to me to be honorable citizens, so far as I know haven't committed a crime and I don't want to make a disclosure.", "start": 2781.777, "stop": 2795.438, "duration": 13.66}, {"text": "You could ask him too much for the Committee then either to expound the question, make it clear and not have to the witness or if it gets beyond that to have the courts not rest on any presumption, presumably (Inaudible) company had laudable legislative purpose.", "start": 2795.438, "stop": 2812.738, "duration": 17.3}, {"text": "Will that be asking too much?", "start": 2812.738, "stop": 2815.308, "duration": 2.57}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, I think the record shows that they -- they thought there was a clear understanding of the question that was being asked and their purpose in asking.", "start": 2815.308, "stop": 2826.106, "duration": 10.8}, {"text": "So that I think the record shows that they were not trying in anyway to be unfair to anyone if there's a mutual understanding.", "start": 2826.106, "stop": 2834.837, "duration": 8.73}, {"text": "He understands on his legal grounds whatever they were and they felt that there was no other answer.", "start": 2834.837, "stop": 2840.898, "duration": 6.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your answer to my question is that this record satisfies those implications of fairness that I have put to you?", "start": 2840.898, "stop": 2848.354, "duration": 7.46}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think they did Mr. Justice.", "start": 2848.354, "stop": 2848.608, "duration": 0.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's your answer.", "start": 2848.608, "stop": 2852.208, "duration": 3.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Rauh.", "start": 2852.208, "stop": 2854.596, "duration": 2.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Justice Frankfurter, the provision on the Subcommittee is that whoever is in the room is a Subcommittee.", "start": 2854.596, "stop": 2860.8, "duration": 6.2}, {"text": "That is actually shown by the record here that whoever happens to be present at even after recess, the Chairman says at this point is a Subcommittee.", "start": 2860.8, "stop": 2869.324, "duration": 8.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that's not for us to criticize or (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 2869.324, "stop": 2871.051, "duration": 1.73}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I agree.", "start": 2871.051, "stop": 2872.175, "duration": 1.12}, {"text": "I was only saying --", "start": 2872.175, "stop": 2873.089, "duration": 0.91}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, I understand.", "start": 2873.089, "stop": 2873.693, "duration": 0.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- that neither Subcommittee, because there were two, actually here, nor this Committee has ever suggested the relevance of the questions we have been asked.", "start": 2873.693, "stop": 2883.018, "duration": 9.32}, {"text": "Now, I would suggest to Your Honors that the Solicitor General's very clear statement here indicates very dangerous of retroactive rationalization that I have referred to before.", "start": 2883.018, "stop": 2898.037, "duration": 15.02}, {"text": "I was at the Committee in the trial court, the Court of Appeals and I read the briefs in this case, that suggested that Rumsey's testimony was connected with our testimony in the sense that that sentence about propaganda was ever put to us, has never been mentioned in any document in this case until we came in this Court and heard this, this morning.", "start": 2898.037, "stop": 2919.906, "duration": 21.87}, {"text": "In others words, what I am suggesting is that the very point I was making has been demonstrated, you can always look for something somewhere that wasn't told to the witness but that somebody else could say might have been relevant, had it been told to the witness.", "start": 2919.906, "stop": 2932.939, "duration": 13.03}, {"text": "Now, maybe Rumsey and Spencer testified two years before.", "start": 2932.939, "stop": 2938.749, "duration": 5.81}, {"text": "Rumsey testified six to eight weeks before the witness, that suggested this witness was in some way connected with the subsidy of parts of that testimony, I do not see.", "start": 2938.749, "stop": 2949.1, "duration": 10.35}, {"text": "They didn't ask him one question about any substantive thing they had asked Rumsey and Spencer.", "start": 2949.1, "stop": 2955.193, "duration": 6.09}, {"text": "They only asked him to name these people.", "start": 2955.193, "stop": 2957.743, "duration": 2.55}, {"text": "Now, I'd like to answer Mr. Justice Brennan's question on that -- on that point.", "start": 2957.743, "stop": 2962.506, "duration": 4.76}, {"text": "I would take -- take it was did not -- when he denied the thing about himself, didn't he then bring into question, the credibility of Rumsey and Spencer about these other people.", "start": 2962.506, "stop": 2974.076, "duration": 11.57}, {"text": "Of course he did.", "start": 2974.076, "stop": 2975.098, "duration": 1.02}, {"text": "I -- I readily say that.", "start": 2975.098, "stop": 2977.602, "duration": 2.5}, {"text": "But unless building that list of Communist in the mid-1940's was a legislative purpose, then he couldn't be required to go into that.", "start": 2977.602, "stop": 2992.229, "duration": 14.63}, {"text": "For example, suppose I want to go before the -- a committee, these were voluntary witnesses.", "start": 2992.229, "stop": 2998.497, "duration": 6.27}, {"text": "Suppose I want to go before the House on American Activities Committee and I want to name everybody in this room as Communist, I can do that.", "start": 2998.497, "stop": 3007.279, "duration": 8.78}, {"text": "There's no way anybody can stop me.", "start": 3007.279, "stop": 3009.423, "duration": 2.14}, {"text": "I then have a privilege against libel and slander in doing it and then they subpoena my associate.", "start": 3009.423, "stop": 3016.34, "duration": 6.92}, {"text": "There had been no legislative purpose in my going before.", "start": 3016.34, "stop": 3018.985, "duration": 2.64}, {"text": "It had been a clearly intended exposure by me and the Committee.", "start": 3018.985, "stop": 3023.76, "duration": 4.78}, {"text": "Then they subpoena my associate and they asked her if all of these people were Communist, and she says, \"I would not.", "start": 3023.76, "stop": 3033.553, "duration": 9.79}, {"text": "I cannot answer this.", "start": 3033.553, "stop": 3034.768, "duration": 1.22}, {"text": "I cannot inform on them.\"", "start": 3034.768, "stop": 3036.622, "duration": 1.85}, {"text": "The fact that I have been a willing tool of the exposure of the Committee does not give them a right to subpoena somebody else and force them to be a tool of the Committee to determine whether the willing tool of exposure was in fact engaged in a legislative purpose.", "start": 3036.622, "stop": 3053.104, "duration": 16.48}, {"text": "In other words, the fact that Rumsey and Spencer were willing tools of the House Committee on the exposure point does not make petitioner when he goes before them, require to answer questions that were asked for exposure.", "start": 3053.104, "stop": 3068.809, "duration": 15.71}, {"text": "So it seems to me that where the Solicitor General and I find company is not -- not the petitioner had in questions the credibility of Rumsey and Spencer, of course he had.", "start": 3068.809, "stop": 3080.091, "duration": 11.28}, {"text": "Although, I would point out that there is no question of petitioner's credibility in this case.", "start": 3080.091, "stop": 3085.535, "duration": 5.44}, {"text": "First, because of the fact that it's a contempt case and they did not take any action against him, and second, and I would ask Your Honors to look at page 59 of the Government's brief.", "start": 3085.535, "stop": 3095.463, "duration": 9.93}, {"text": "There is a statement at the bottom of the page, beginning of the second paragraph on page 59 which is very important related to this, a more complete and candid statement of his, \"That the petitioner passed political associations and activities can hardly be imagined.”", "start": 3095.463, "stop": 3117.453, "duration": 21.99}, {"text": "Now here, the Government is saying, \"This fellow was willing to tell everything.\"", "start": 3117.453, "stop": 3122.124, "duration": 4.67}, {"text": "Of course they said this in order to prove we didn't have a First Amendment right.", "start": 3122.124, "stop": 3125.638, "duration": 3.51}, {"text": "But they said, you could hardly imagine a man that's been more candid about this and yet they want to say, nevertheless, he has got to answer questions and become a tool of exposure because Mr. Rumsey and Spencer were willing to be tools of exposure.", "start": 3125.638, "stop": 3143.056, "duration": 17.42}, {"text": "I suggest to Your Honors that Rumsey and Spencer could have refused to answer those questions on the same grounds that the only purpose -- the purpose made in the Government's brief was to build a list of Communist in 1945.", "start": 3143.056, "stop": 3155.978, "duration": 12.92}, {"text": "If they could have refused to answer those questions because of the ground of exposure, the fact that they were a wiling tool of it doesn't make him a necessary part of it.", "start": 3155.978, "stop": 3164.309, "duration": 8.33}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Rauh, in that Section, assuming a legislative purpose for this.", "start": 3164.309, "stop": 3168.805, "duration": 4.5}, {"text": "What do you have to say to the Solicitor General's suggestion that the First Amendment is to protect when you open your mouth but not to keep it closed?", "start": 3168.805, "stop": 3176.098, "duration": 7.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I was going to come to that, sir.", "start": 3176.098, "stop": 3177.408, "duration": 1.31}, {"text": "I think, Your Honors, settle that in the Rumely case.", "start": 3177.408, "stop": 3180.667, "duration": 3.26}, {"text": "I do not feel that the -- I feel the Solicitor General is rearguing the decision of this Court in the Rumely case and the dictum of this Court in Quinn.", "start": 3180.667, "stop": 3192.801, "duration": 12.13}, {"text": "If Your Honors please, in the Quinn case, in a dictum that Chief Justice Warren did refer to the Bill of Rights as covering the entire -- as covering this field.", "start": 3192.801, "stop": 3202.945, "duration": 10.14}, {"text": "But I would think that the Rumely case had some of that matter.", "start": 3202.945, "stop": 3205.867, "duration": 2.92}, {"text": "I don't think it was enough for me to reargue but I want to answer the second question you put to the Solicitor General if I may and that was about this legislation that was passed.", "start": 3205.867, "stop": 3216.881, "duration": 11.01}, {"text": "Now, if Your Honor pleases, about the report of that -- on that Committee, I'd like to call your attention to page 73 of our initial white brief.", "start": 3216.881, "stop": 3228.565, "duration": 11.68}, {"text": "The Committee's report on the bill, to which the court below refers, did not claim there had been any hearings on the bill.", "start": 3228.565, "stop": 3236.08, "duration": 7.51}, {"text": "The minority reports stated categorically that no hearings had been held.", "start": 3236.08, "stop": 3241.266, "duration": 5.19}, {"text": "One of this minority, who stated that no hearings had been held, Congress embraced it was present of the petitioner's interrogation, it would have been a position and know if the question had been directed in any way of that Amendment.", "start": 3241.266, "stop": 3252.495, "duration": 11.23}, {"text": "In other words, this legislation was pending and was inactive, but that doesn't of it -- in it of itself demonstrate that this questioning was related to that legislation.", "start": 3252.495, "stop": 3265.052, "duration": 12.56}, {"text": "It is only related if you are wiling to say or if someone is willing to say that they had to know or they had a right to know the exact number of Communist 10 years before in order to determine whether to pass a law in a different situation at a later time, and when -- and this I cannot repeat too often, and when the Committee itself -- remember this is the Government saying what the Committee thought, not what the Committee itself is saying it thought.", "start": 3265.052, "stop": 3297.719, "duration": 32.67}, {"text": "What the Committee itself did, namely in never asking this fellow how many Communist were in the union, in never asking him whether he could name others, they never asking him -- they never show the slightest indication in take of -- that they were taking the retroactive census that the Government now claims (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 3297.719, "stop": 3313.824, "duration": 16.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "But now, you're -- you're -- what you've just said the last few minutes, what you previously said, that this -- that justice in the lower court, the trial before a judge, any questions that are logically relevant, remotely so, but logically relevant are not allowed to be asked, the offense, the area of relevance is fenced in an inquiry before a court.", "start": 3313.824, "stop": 3337.786, "duration": 23.96}, {"text": "So you now say that the area of relevance before a congressional committee, no matter how loose you are is fenced in by the turns of the resolution and if you go beyond that by the separation of powers, is that what your argument is?", "start": 3337.786, "stop": 3349.125, "duration": 11.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 3349.125, "stop": 3351.04, "duration": 1.91}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "It really gets down to that, doesn't it?", "start": 3351.04, "stop": 3353.214, "duration": 2.17}, {"text": "That this is unrelated to the allowable range of relevant inquiry with you to do the subject matter with which this commission -- Committee was charged?", "start": 3353.214, "stop": 3364.354, "duration": 11.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's correct, if Your Honor please.", "start": 3364.354, "stop": 3366.031, "duration": 1.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Isn't that -- is that it?", "start": 3366.031, "stop": 3367.086, "duration": 1.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, and then I'd say I go from there --", "start": 3367.086, "stop": 3371.283, "duration": 4.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 3371.283, "stop": 3371.868, "duration": 0.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- to the point that even if they were within the allowable relevance --", "start": 3371.868, "stop": 3377.357, "duration": 5.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's been.", "start": 3377.357, "stop": 3377.987, "duration": 0.63}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- in the sub -- sense of the separation of power, there has been no suggested need which could anyway offset their oppressive effect.", "start": 3377.987, "stop": 3386.762, "duration": 8.78}, {"text": "And I think here we come and I would like to -- I'm sure the Solicitor General did not mean to --", "start": 3386.762, "stop": 3393.344, "duration": 6.58}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that's like -- that's like ruling out, waiving the body shape trial.", "start": 3393.344, "stop": 3397.634, "duration": 4.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 3397.634, "stop": 3397.837, "duration": 0.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "That it may have some relevance but it's too costly.", "start": 3397.837, "stop": 3401.604, "duration": 3.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "That is precisely our point, and if Your Honor please, I'm sure the Solicitor General didn't mean to misstate this but I do think it's important on the question of when we raised the First Amendment point.", "start": 3401.604, "stop": 3415.069, "duration": 13.47}, {"text": "I'm sorry but, we sure did raise it.", "start": 3415.069, "stop": 3417.869, "duration": 2.8}, {"text": "If you look on page 55 of the -- of our -- of the record, I like to call Your Honors attention to point number 14, in which I say point number 14 is the First Amendment argument that we have made here.", "start": 3417.869, "stop": 3434.507, "duration": 16.64}, {"text": "I think we made until the 15 point.", "start": 3434.507, "stop": 3436.302, "duration": 1.8}, {"text": "I am sure Your Honor is familiar with it.", "start": 3436.302, "stop": 3437.593, "duration": 1.29}, {"text": "The point never passed on by the Supreme Court and I think the reason for avoiding it in the Rumely case is that brought that narrow construction.", "start": 3437.593, "stop": 3443.63, "duration": 6.04}, {"text": "It was up again last Monday with Quinn and Emspak cases were there and it is more than somewhat in this case.", "start": 3443.63, "stop": 3449.223, "duration": 5.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, is it -- practically to be assumed that in a case like this or anything like it, any lawyer, particularly you, you've raised the First Amendment point (Inaudible) is that right?", "start": 3449.223, "stop": 3460.618, "duration": 11.39}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "I thought it was still -- as I pointed out that I had raised it sir.", "start": 3460.618, "stop": 3464.4, "duration": 3.78}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "I thought he said in the hearing?", "start": 3464.4, "stop": 3466.058, "duration": 1.66}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh, well --", "start": 3466.058, "stop": 3466.91, "duration": 0.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, he may.", "start": 3466.91, "stop": 3467.519, "duration": 0.61}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "He said first it raised here and then in the Court of Appeals.", "start": 3467.519, "stop": 3470.259, "duration": 2.74}, {"text": "Now, as to the question on raising it at the hearing, I suggest Your Honors that if you will look at page 85, we raised everything we could.", "start": 3470.259, "stop": 3479.408, "duration": 9.15}, {"text": "We -- we raised -- we raised everything.", "start": 3479.408, "stop": 3483.034, "duration": 3.63}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "You've got a form letter, haven't you?", "start": 3483.034, "stop": 3484.886, "duration": 1.85}, {"text": "[Laughter]", "start": 3484.886, "stop": 3487.416, "duration": 2.53}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I wouldn't put it exactly that way.", "start": 3487.416, "stop": 3489.991, "duration": 2.57}, {"text": "I would only -- I would only suggest that we did raise every point of our power and right to suggest that you had to use those two words, particularly to this Court which has allowed the plea of the Fifth Amendment which is a much more specific thing which has to be raised to suggest we had to use those exact words.", "start": 3489.991, "stop": 3510.344, "duration": 20.35}, {"text": "I -- I rather doubt there was no indication of any decision of this Court that those exact words would have happen to use.", "start": 3510.344, "stop": 3516.669, "duration": 6.32}, {"text": "And we certainly were trying to do it.", "start": 3516.669, "stop": 3520.137, "duration": 3.47}, {"text": "I have no doubt that we did raise it and we raised each stage in the trial.", "start": 3520.137, "stop": 3524.846, "duration": 4.71}, {"text": "Now, in conclusion there is, I take it, made your point of deference to Congress and I'm second to -- not willing to be second to the Solicitor General in feeling that there should a deference to Congress in this area.", "start": 3524.846, "stop": 3543.794, "duration": 18.95}, {"text": "But the problem arises when Congress seeks to utilize the criminal processes, where an individual has the right to raise these points.", "start": 3543.794, "stop": 3555.208, "duration": 11.41}, {"text": "Now, Mr. Justice -- the Solicitor General in answer to Mr. Justice Brennan's question said, “Yes, in the field of communism, the only area you can defend on is the Fifth Amendment.”", "start": 3555.208, "stop": 3567.966, "duration": 12.76}, {"text": "Now, I just don't believe that the decisions of this Court hold anything like that or that the -- or possibly could hold that.", "start": 3567.966, "stop": 3576.104, "duration": 8.14}, {"text": "There is a weighing under the Fifth -- First Amendment that is necessary.", "start": 3576.104, "stop": 3580.216, "duration": 4.11}, {"text": "There is the vagueness that must be considered.", "start": 3580.216, "stop": 3582.483, "duration": 2.27}, {"text": "There is the exposure that -- that must be considered.", "start": 3582.483, "stop": 3585.665, "duration": 3.18}, {"text": "It seems to me to say that anybody who is ever in anyway got in one foot anywhere near the Communist movement has lost all his rights against criminal prosecution for refusing to answer questions is to say that if we had taken one area out of American life and said there and there only there are no defenses in refusing to answer questions.", "start": 3585.665, "stop": 3608.101, "duration": 22.44}, {"text": "Now, I suggest that Your Honors had settled that in the Sinclair case.", "start": 3608.101, "stop": 3612.169, "duration": 4.07}, {"text": "I thought that that had really settled the point on which this Court said it knows on certain terms that the presumption of validity is great but the presumption of innocence is greater.", "start": 3612.169, "stop": 3626.774, "duration": 14.61}, {"text": "And it seems to me that that's exactly what we have here.", "start": 3626.774, "stop": 3629.424, "duration": 2.65}, {"text": "Congress wants to require answers at the Bar of the House, there are certain rights that they have.", "start": 3629.424, "stop": 3636.419, "duration": 6.99}, {"text": "I do not have that case before me.", "start": 3636.419, "stop": 3638.514, "duration": 2.1}, {"text": "I do not know the extent of those rights.", "start": 3638.514, "stop": 3641.037, "duration": 2.52}, {"text": "But when they prosecute criminal for a question, where the relevance has never been stated by the Committee and where a different relevance is presented every time I go to a different court with this case and I hear a different effort to rationalize this reason for these questions, I can only feel it seems to me, perfectly clear that the only possible reason for asking a man the names of whether certain persons were Communists in the 19 -- mid-1940's.", "start": 3641.037, "stop": 3673.618, "duration": 32.58}, {"text": "We're Asking him that 10 years later was an effort to expose him and them to scorn and ridicule.", "start": 3673.618, "stop": 3709.381, "duration": 35.76}]}]}, {"transcriptTitle": "Oral Argument - March 07, 1957 (Part 1)", "transcriptLink": "https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren5/oral_argument_audio/13340", "transcript": [{"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Number 261, John T. Watkins, Petitioner versus United States of America.", "start": 0, "stop": 37.293, "duration": 37.29}, {"text": "Mr. Rauh, you may proceed.", "start": 37.293, "stop": 43.608, "duration": 6.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "May it please the Court.", "start": 43.608, "stop": 45.671, "duration": 2.06}, {"text": "This case is here on petition for certiorari to review a decision of a full bench of the Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit which had reversed a three-judge panel.", "start": 45.671, "stop": 59.681, "duration": 14.01}, {"text": "The three-judge panel had reversed petitioner's conviction for contempt of Congress in the full bench with the two judges dissenting, reversed the panel and affirmed petitioner's conviction.", "start": 59.681, "stop": 74.14, "duration": 14.46}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "The panel thing is not printed, is it?", "start": 74.14, "stop": 76.357, "duration": 2.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir, but it is substantially identical with the dissenting opinion and there is a footnote in the dissenting opinion --", "start": 76.357, "stop": 83.409, "duration": 7.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 83.409, "stop": 83.795, "duration": 0.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- stating that it is substantially identical.", "start": 83.795, "stop": 85.803, "duration": 2.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Both the majority and the minority in this case?", "start": 85.803, "stop": 87.475, "duration": 1.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 87.475, "stop": 88.448, "duration": 0.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "The panel consisted of (Inaudible)", "start": 88.448, "stop": 91.978, "duration": 3.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir and the dissenting opinion of Judge Baskin became the majority opinion after the reversal.", "start": 91.978, "stop": 98.265, "duration": 6.29}, {"text": "The essential facts are these.", "start": 98.265, "stop": 100.959, "duration": 2.69}, {"text": "Petitioner was subpoenaed to appear and did appear before the House Committee on Un-American Activities in April 1954.", "start": 100.959, "stop": 110.621, "duration": 9.66}, {"text": "Now, before he appeared, two witnesses had appeared before that Committee, one several years before and one recently before and had identified him as a Communist during the middle 1940's.", "start": 110.621, "stop": 128.777, "duration": 18.16}, {"text": "Now, at the opening of his hearing which was in Washington D.C. on April 1954, the Chairman simply -- of the Committee simply announced, “We're here in continuation of what happened to Chicago.”", "start": 128.777, "stop": 141.947, "duration": 13.17}, {"text": "Now, that was a hearing some six weeks before.", "start": 141.947, "stop": 144.98, "duration": 3.03}, {"text": "Now that, at the outset of the hearing in Chicago, the Chairman of the Committee had made a lengthy pro-formal -- formal opening statement listing past and pending bills and giving the general aims and purposes of the Committee in this hearing and there will be more of that opening statement later.", "start": 144.98, "stop": 168.362, "duration": 23.38}, {"text": "Now, at the hearing, petitioner testified freely and fully about himself.", "start": 168.362, "stop": 175.586, "duration": 7.22}, {"text": "He affirmed his cooperation with the Communist Party during the years, 1942 to 1947.", "start": 175.586, "stop": 185.569, "duration": 9.98}, {"text": "1942 to 1947, he said “I cooperated with them.", "start": 185.569, "stop": 190.116, "duration": 4.55}, {"text": "I was so close to him that some of them might honestly have believed I was part of them, but I didn't join.”", "start": 190.116, "stop": 196.338, "duration": 6.22}, {"text": "He testified that in 1947, the middle of 1947 at a convention of his union which was then the Farm Equipment Workers, he got in such a bitter battle with the Communist over the question of compliance with the non-Communist oath provisions of Taft-Hartley this cooperation was over and from then on, he's been an anti-Communist.", "start": 196.338, "stop": 221.517, "duration": 25.18}, {"text": "But after telling them all about himself, then it has come to all witnesses before the House of Un-American Activities Committee, he was asked the name certain other persons who in -- in the mid-1940's had been members of the Communist Party and it was here and here only that petitioner bought.", "start": 221.517, "stop": 246.226, "duration": 24.71}, {"text": "Now, on page 85 of the record is his statement.", "start": 246.226, "stop": 251.76, "duration": 5.53}, {"text": "“When he refused to say whether certain persons had been members of the Communist Party in the middle 1940's, I would like to get one thing perfectly clear Mr. Chairman, I am not going to plead the Firth Amendment.”", "start": 251.76, "stop": 267.173, "duration": 15.41}, {"text": "I would just like to -- to interpolate here for the Courts, for the clarity of the position and the problem of the petitioner.", "start": 267.173, "stop": 280.129, "duration": 12.96}, {"text": "At the time he made his decision on what to do before this Committee, he had only three alternatives.", "start": 280.129, "stop": 288.575, "duration": 8.45}, {"text": "This Court's decision in the Rogers case, made it impossible for him to do what might very well have been his first choice.", "start": 288.575, "stop": 297.617, "duration": 9.04}, {"text": "Namely, to have told all about himself and pleaded the Fifth Amendment when it came to informing on others.", "start": 297.617, "stop": 304.524, "duration": 6.91}, {"text": "That is not as he was informed a legal possibility.", "start": 304.524, "stop": 309.151, "duration": 4.63}, {"text": "The Fifth Amendment is not available.", "start": 309.151, "stop": 311.663, "duration": 2.51}, {"text": "The self-incrimination provisions are not available, if you have already incriminated yourself by the -- under the (Inaudible) case.", "start": 311.663, "stop": 320.423, "duration": 8.76}, {"text": "So, his choices, with that choice ruled out were these three, he could have known all the information from the Committee by pleading the Fifth Amendment as to his own personal activities and also as to the others and it is this Court's decisions in the (Inaudible) cases.", "start": 320.423, "stop": 336.003, "duration": 15.58}, {"text": "It was clear he had this right or he could have told everything.", "start": 336.003, "stop": 340.493, "duration": 4.49}, {"text": "Namely, he could have told all about himself and he could have named the others.", "start": 340.493, "stop": 345.611, "duration": 5.12}, {"text": "As to this, he would then been an informer, the worst crime he can commit among his own associates.", "start": 345.611, "stop": 352.195, "duration": 6.58}, {"text": "And the third, the third is to tell about yourself, which he was not ashamed of it, which he was willing and did do and then say, this is what he did choose.", "start": 352.195, "stop": 362.086, "duration": 9.89}, {"text": "This was the third alternative.", "start": 362.086, "stop": 363.497, "duration": 1.41}, {"text": "“You don't have power to force me to name the other persons, because it's beyond your jurisdiction and because you are engaged in exposure.”", "start": 363.497, "stop": 372.085, "duration": 8.59}, {"text": "And this is what he said then as he chose the alternative.", "start": 372.085, "stop": 376.383, "duration": 4.3}, {"text": "“I would like to get one thing perfectly clear Mr. Chairman.", "start": 376.383, "stop": 379.473, "duration": 3.09}, {"text": "I am not going to plead the Fifth Amendment, but I refuse to answer certain questions that I believe are outside the proper scope of your Committee's activities.", "start": 379.473, "stop": 388.683, "duration": 9.21}, {"text": "I will answer any questions which this Committee puts to be about myself.", "start": 388.683, "stop": 392.851, "duration": 4.17}, {"text": "I will also answer questions about those persons whom I knew to be members to the Communist Party and whom I believed still are.", "start": 392.851, "stop": 399.566, "duration": 6.71}, {"text": "I will not, however, answer any questions with respect to others with whom I associated in the past,” then I skip.", "start": 399.566, "stop": 406.694, "duration": 7.13}, {"text": "“I do not believe that such questions are relevant to the work of this Committee nor do I believe that this Committee has the right to undertake the public exposure of persons because of their past activities.”", "start": 406.694, "stop": 420.114, "duration": 13.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, he do (Inaudible) then you indicated a minute ago.", "start": 420.114, "stop": 424.151, "duration": 4.04}, {"text": "He would inform you that word as to those whom you regarded a Communist.", "start": 424.151, "stop": 429.638, "duration": 5.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's correct, sir, I did.", "start": 429.638, "stop": 430.874, "duration": 1.24}, {"text": "It is narrower than I stated.", "start": 430.874, "stop": 433.491, "duration": 2.62}, {"text": "Now, when petitioner finished his statement, the Committee did not contradict his assertion that they were engaged in public exposure.", "start": 433.491, "stop": 443.254, "duration": 9.76}, {"text": "The Chairman simply paraphrased the Committee's resolution and said, “Answer”.", "start": 443.254, "stop": 449.825, "duration": 6.57}, {"text": "“Petitioner stuck to his prepared statement.", "start": 449.825, "stop": 452.532, "duration": 2.71}, {"text": "They asked him a numbers of 30 odd people.", "start": 452.532, "stop": 456.865, "duration": 4.33}, {"text": "He is stuck to his ground, but he would not name those in the past who he no longer felt were members of the Party.”", "start": 456.865, "stop": 465.746, "duration": 8.88}, {"text": "Here, the Committee had before him an expert in Communist activities in the labor movement.", "start": 465.746, "stop": 472.054, "duration": 6.31}, {"text": "But when he refused to inform on these others not one more question, not one question about Communist techniques in the labor movement, he was discharged.", "start": 472.054, "stop": 483.845, "duration": 11.79}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Are the -- are the questions that were refused, all in relation to his knowledge of named persons --", "start": 483.845, "stop": 490.867, "duration": 7.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 490.867, "stop": 491.379, "duration": 0.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- or any other question?", "start": 491.379, "stop": 492.929, "duration": 1.55}, {"text": "No other --", "start": 492.929, "stop": 493.315, "duration": 0.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "All in -- yes.", "start": 493.315, "stop": 494.364, "duration": 1.05}, {"text": "The answer to your question is -- is yes.", "start": 494.364, "stop": 496.085, "duration": 1.72}, {"text": "There were no other questions in the indictment except those as to --", "start": 496.085, "stop": 499.512, "duration": 3.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Merely a series of names about who he was interrogated and as to whom he refused to open his mouth?", "start": 499.512, "stop": 505.569, "duration": 6.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Precisely.", "start": 505.569, "stop": 506.083, "duration": 0.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's the whole case?", "start": 506.083, "stop": 506.966, "duration": 0.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 506.966, "stop": 508.381, "duration": 1.41}, {"text": "Petitioner was cited and indicted on seven counts for contempt to Congress.", "start": 508.381, "stop": 512.335, "duration": 3.95}, {"text": "He was tried without a jury at the trial.", "start": 512.335, "stop": 515.827, "duration": 3.49}, {"text": "Petitioner sought to prove that the purpose of the Committee had been solely one of exposure, by which I mean injurious publicity had been the sole purpose of the Committee.", "start": 515.827, "stop": 526.529, "duration": 10.7}, {"text": "And if petitioner sought to prove this through three avenues approved.", "start": 526.529, "stop": 531.932, "duration": 5.4}, {"text": "One, official statements and reports of the Committee in the members of the Committee on official business that the Un-American Activities Committee asserts this right of exposure independent of any legislative purpose.", "start": 531.932, "stop": 548.906, "duration": 16.97}, {"text": "Secondly, that the questioning of petitioner and his colloquies with the Committee demonstrated this purpose of exposure.", "start": 548.906, "stop": 555.627, "duration": 6.72}, {"text": "And thirdly, that the Committee had all the information and sought that petitioner has filed and didn't even bother to examine.", "start": 555.627, "stop": 563.063, "duration": 7.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "May interrupt you once more?", "start": 563.063, "stop": 565.021, "duration": 1.96}, {"text": "Did the Committee walk into the door that he opened and say, “You stated you're ready to testify about former communists and those who still are, we now advise you that the Committee has good reason for believing that Jones, Smith, Robinson, et cetera are within that category.", "start": 565.021, "stop": 587.828, "duration": 22.81}, {"text": "You may have it with information, on the basis of our information, we now press these questions.”", "start": 587.828, "stop": 592.789, "duration": 4.96}, {"text": "Is there anything like that?", "start": 592.789, "stop": 593.755, "duration": 0.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I must admit that the -- that the Committee, that two of these two people who have identified him had also identified most of them.", "start": 593.755, "stop": 602.834, "duration": 9.08}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, but I mean the Chairman?", "start": 602.834, "stop": 604.308, "duration": 1.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, there is nothing said by that.", "start": 604.308, "stop": 604.982, "duration": 0.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm not talking about anything outside.", "start": 604.982, "stop": 606.536, "duration": 1.55}, {"text": "The Chairman, after this statement, if the Chairman say, “Accepting your position, accepting your -- a certain withdraw about yourself, we do like to inform you we're pressing these questions because we have reason to believe they come within your vow of readiness to testify.”", "start": 606.536, "stop": 624.116, "duration": 17.58}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 624.116, "stop": 624.506, "duration": 0.39}, {"text": "That goes with no such reference at all.", "start": 624.506, "stop": 625.936, "duration": 1.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "He simply asked.", "start": 625.936, "stop": 626.897, "duration": 0.96}, {"text": "“We want to ask you about John Smith,” and he said, “I won't talk about it.”", "start": 626.897, "stop": 629.798, "duration": 2.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Precisely.", "start": 629.798, "stop": 631.04, "duration": 1.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Without any qualification --", "start": 631.04, "stop": 632.102, "duration": 1.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Precisely.", "start": 632.102, "stop": 632.699, "duration": 0.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- that they drew the circle and -- and stuck to it and he was --", "start": 632.699, "stop": 637.227, "duration": 4.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "He was asked the question with about 25 names in it and he pulled one name out of it and said, “That fellow is still is and I won't answer as to the rest.”", "start": 637.227, "stop": 645.872, "duration": 8.64}, {"text": "Now, the trial court held that all of the petitioner's evidence and proof of exposure was irrelevant, apparently and I say apparently because the district judge did not give his reasons for any of his rulings nor for the conviction.", "start": 645.872, "stop": 658.885, "duration": 13.01}, {"text": "Apparently, accepting a prosecuting attorney's position which I could phrase as follows, “Fifth Amendment or nothing, it is the position of the Government in the trial courts,” although I am not quite as clear that it is their position here, although it is quite close to it that the only defense to a contempt of Congress indictment in this area of Communism is the Fifth Amendment.", "start": 658.885, "stop": 686.159, "duration": 27.27}, {"text": "That was squarely stated by the prosecuting attorney in the lower court here and it was apparently and I say apparently because the judge did not say anything except, “Your evidence is excluded,” the disposition of the court below.", "start": 686.159, "stop": 702.406, "duration": 16.25}, {"text": "Now, the petitioner was convicted.", "start": 702.406, "stop": 704.158, "duration": 1.75}, {"text": "He appealed as I said before of the three-judge panel, the conviction was reversed, then there was a reversal of the reversal and the conviction was affirmed 62.", "start": 704.158, "stop": 717.931, "duration": 13.77}, {"text": "Those are believed are the essential facts.", "start": 717.931, "stop": 723.081, "duration": 5.15}, {"text": "The first point we lay before, Your Honors, I do not believe we need to elaborate on to any great extent.", "start": 723.081, "stop": 730.898, "duration": 7.82}, {"text": "It's made in our initial and our reply brief and it is that the power to investigate does not encompass exposure unrelated to a legislative purpose.", "start": 730.898, "stop": 743.826, "duration": 12.93}, {"text": "And when I say I don't believe we need to pause long on this point, I say it because it is an obvious corollary of the doctrine of separation of powers.", "start": 743.826, "stop": 755.593, "duration": 11.77}, {"text": "And also, because I do not understand the Government to -- seriously to contest the proposition, that exposure -- for exposure sake is beyond detail.", "start": 755.593, "stop": 766.333, "duration": 10.74}, {"text": "Now, the proposition, it seems to me is simple.", "start": 766.333, "stop": 770.313, "duration": 3.98}, {"text": "The legislative function is to determine general standards of conduct.", "start": 770.313, "stop": 776.291, "duration": 5.98}, {"text": "The executive function is to prosecute for infractions of the general standard of conduct and the judicial function is to determine guilt when a congressional committee determined a standard of conduct to debar, namely past membership in the Communist Party and then, through exposure by calling him before them, prosecutes him, forces him to answer.", "start": 776.291, "stop": 805.925, "duration": 29.63}, {"text": "And then finally, through the determination of guilt by their accusation of him and their reports about him, keeps injurious publicity upon him, they are combining all three functions in one.", "start": 805.925, "stop": 821.747, "duration": 15.82}, {"text": "I would suggest to Your Honors, we use the different example in our brief but supposed we went back to the 1910s, during the period when Mr. Mann was considering and bringing before the Congress, the Mann Act.", "start": 821.747, "stop": 836.088, "duration": 14.34}, {"text": "Supposed at that time, he had felt, “I cannot get a bill through Congress.”", "start": 836.088, "stop": 840.492, "duration": 4.4}, {"text": "Suppose he had felt that President Wilson, I believed it was, would not have sign such a bill and indeed he didn't have the votes to pass it over a veto, but he says to himself.", "start": 840.492, "stop": 852.605, "duration": 12.11}, {"text": "“I can accomplish the same thing by simply calling before the -- our Committee.", "start": 852.605, "stop": 859.745, "duration": 7.14}, {"text": "I'll get a right to investigate and I'll call before the Committee everybody I can find who I have any suspicion may pass in the past have violated the Mann Act, what is now the Mann Act.”", "start": 859.745, "stop": 873.714, "duration": 13.97}, {"text": "In other words, supposed Mr. Mann had sought to do by injurious publicity exactly what they did by legislation.", "start": 873.714, "stop": 882.129, "duration": 8.41}, {"text": "I think this Court would have had no hesitancy in striking that down as an effort to accomplish without legislation to substitute purposes of legislation.", "start": 882.129, "stop": 891.887, "duration": 9.76}, {"text": "Now, the Government does make two tangential points about this so I'd like to refer to, although as I -- I honestly believe they are not in --in wholehearted disagreement on this point.", "start": 891.887, "stop": 905.523, "duration": 13.64}, {"text": "First, the Government refers to the quote, “informing function” of Congress as one that has been written up in the books, although admittedly, not in the books of this Court.", "start": 905.523, "stop": 920.06, "duration": 14.54}, {"text": "Now, that of course phrase, “informing function” goes back to President Wilson at the time he wrote his great text on the subject of Congress, but President Wilson's reference to the informing function was to something different.", "start": 920.06, "stop": 935.195, "duration": 15.14}, {"text": "It was to the internal debates and give and take within Congress.", "start": 935.195, "stop": 940.204, "duration": 5.01}, {"text": "Indeed, President Wilson's illustration of the informing function was the question and answer period in the House of Commons about as far away from the idea of compulsory testimony being used for the informing function as possible.", "start": 940.204, "stop": 958.529, "duration": 18.33}, {"text": "Now, it is true when the Government cites a number of articles at page 55 of its brief that President Wilson's informing function has carried over in some articles, never ratified by this Court to suggest an informing function in another category.", "start": 958.529, "stop": 977.384, "duration": 18.86}, {"text": "And here, it is in the supervision of public administration.", "start": 977.384, "stop": 982.362, "duration": 4.98}, {"text": "Now, I do not have to carry the burden before this Court to argue that there is or isn't such an informing function when it comes to the supervision of the executive branch in the administration of law in America, because we do not have that case here.", "start": 982.362, "stop": 1002.335, "duration": 19.97}, {"text": "Here, we do not have the informing function of a supervision of public administration.", "start": 1002.335, "stop": 1008.017, "duration": 5.68}, {"text": "Here, we have the informing function if you seek to call it that.", "start": 1008.017, "stop": 1012.318, "duration": 4.3}, {"text": "Here, we have the exposure, injurious publicity applied to a private citizen.", "start": 1012.318, "stop": 1018.916, "duration": 6.6}, {"text": "Now, the Government also in -- in another tangential point refers to statutes such as the Lobbying Act and the Public Utilities Holding Company Act, where Congress, by statute has required publicity as a method of regulation.", "start": 1018.916, "stop": 1043.204, "duration": 24.29}, {"text": "And I'm prepared to rest our case on the distinction between Congress passing a statute requiring the publicizing of information and a Committee of Congress, maybe a single congressman seeking to accomplish that same result through the subpoena power.", "start": 1043.204, "stop": 1066.742, "duration": 23.54}, {"text": "Now, if Your Honors please, when you have a statute, it's general in application, it's prospective in effect and it's definite in operation.", "start": 1066.742, "stop": 1076.898, "duration": 10.16}, {"text": "When you have congressional committee seek to operate both as legislature judge and jury, then the exposure becomes discriminatory in application, retroactive in effect as it is here and arbitrary in procedure.", "start": 1076.898, "stop": 1094.703, "duration": 17.81}, {"text": "I do not think it is too much to say, but what we have in our case here and what the House Committee's practices have been is that lawmaker investigator, prosecutor, judge and jury, all five reside in the one subcommittee and may reside as it has in the past in one individual.", "start": 1094.703, "stop": 1116.404, "duration": 21.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "How can I tell just from the question that was put that their purpose was or the -- or the scope of the question was nearly to expose?", "start": 1116.404, "stop": 1127.088, "duration": 10.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's point two and I'm -- I'm really right there if --", "start": 1127.088, "stop": 1130.094, "duration": 3.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "All right.", "start": 1130.094, "stop": 1130.715, "duration": 0.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- may I please.", "start": 1130.715, "stop": 1132.203, "duration": 1.49}, {"text": "I just think --", "start": 1132.203, "stop": 1132.836, "duration": 0.63}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "You take your time.", "start": 1132.836, "stop": 1134.074, "duration": 1.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- there is one further observation on the distinction between the Congress engaging by statute requiring the publicizing of certain information.", "start": 1134.074, "stop": 1145.947, "duration": 11.87}, {"text": "Maybe I'm blabbering this too much, but I just like to point out that it does seem to me that it was the blurring of this distinction in the past 10 years, which has caused the concern over the action of congressional committee to which this Court has adverted in both the Rumely and Quinn cases.", "start": 1145.947, "stop": 1168.726, "duration": 22.78}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "I suggest that it's a very almost impossible abstract question that you're asking us -- asking to -- to address ourselves, because you certainly aren't going to urge that they must have an immediate bill in mind, that they must pass an enactment.", "start": 1168.726, "stop": 1185.364, "duration": 16.64}, {"text": "And therefore, we certainly aren't going to argue, I suppose that they can't decide whether they should pass a bill.", "start": 1185.364, "stop": 1191.905, "duration": 6.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Certainly not, if Your Honor please.", "start": 1191.905, "stop": 1193.315, "duration": 1.41}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "And therefore, that has to be preceded by inquiring and once you begin to argue whether that's merely informative or -- or pre-legislative, I don't think it is a very profitable line of inquiry, is it?", "start": 1193.315, "stop": 1204.832, "duration": 11.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think it's -- it's not only profitable.", "start": 1204.832, "stop": 1206.934, "duration": 2.1}, {"text": "I think the entire separation of powers depends upon making this light of inquiry.", "start": 1206.934, "stop": 1213.672, "duration": 6.74}, {"text": "However, I must say that --", "start": 1213.672, "stop": 1214.952, "duration": 1.28}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "That the light of inquiry is that it can't use its activities, merely for purposes of exposure.", "start": 1214.952, "stop": 1220.634, "duration": 5.68}, {"text": "I don't think that needs argument.", "start": 1220.634, "stop": 1222.535, "duration": 1.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well --", "start": 1222.535, "stop": 1222.653, "duration": 0.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "If by your talking, you tell me when it is and when it isn't exposure, that does require --", "start": 1222.653, "stop": 1226.35, "duration": 3.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I -- I just said I may have deliberated too much the -- what I wanted as the hypothesis in which I would make my argument that there was exposure, the fact that no such power exist.", "start": 1226.35, "stop": 1237.401, "duration": 11.05}, {"text": "I -- I now pass to the point two of petitioner's argument.", "start": 1237.401, "stop": 1240.993, "duration": 3.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Congress isn't the U.S. Attorney or an Attorney General.", "start": 1240.993, "stop": 1244.257, "duration": 3.26}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, maybe I should have simply assumed that that was the law that the -- that I couldn't find, just the Hornbrook case to give me that, so I thought I'd better argue with it.", "start": 1244.257, "stop": 1256.035, "duration": 11.78}, {"text": "So, we pass to point two of our argument, which Government does seriously contest and that is that the purpose of the Committee here in interrogating petitioner was to expose him and his former associates to scorn and ridicule.", "start": 1256.035, "stop": 1274.123, "duration": 18.09}, {"text": "Now, if Your Honors please, I'm not bringing to this Court a closed case because I believe that there were closed case about whether it was exposure and legislation.", "start": 1274.123, "stop": 1283.635, "duration": 9.51}, {"text": "A certain deference to Congress might very well warrant that all doubts be resolved in their favor.", "start": 1283.635, "stop": 1289.543, "duration": 5.91}, {"text": "We bring to this case -- this Court a case that if we haven't shown this is exposure for exposure's sake, I honestly believe it can't be shown.", "start": 1289.543, "stop": 1299.094, "duration": 9.55}, {"text": "If Your Honors will read the questioning of petitioner from pages 70 to 90 of this record, you will not find one question of any possible relation to any possible legislation.", "start": 1299.094, "stop": 1318.311, "duration": 19.22}, {"text": "Now, I quite agree with Justice Frankfurter's implication of this question that you may have to ask a lot of questions that are unrelated to a specific bill in order to find out what your legislation ought to be.", "start": 1318.311, "stop": 1333.247, "duration": 14.94}, {"text": "But when -- but here, by both what they asked petitioner and by what they didn't ask him, it's perfectly clear that all they wanted from him were names, names, names of human beings to determine whether in fact they have been Communist in 1945.", "start": 1333.247, "stop": 1357.227, "duration": 23.98}, {"text": "Once, he said, “I will not give you those names.", "start": 1357.227, "stop": 1360.63, "duration": 3.4}, {"text": "I will not tell you where these people were,” they get rid of him.", "start": 1360.63, "stop": 1364.233, "duration": 3.6}, {"text": "They told him they didn't want to ask him anything.", "start": 1364.233, "stop": 1366.45, "duration": 2.22}, {"text": "Now, they didn't have before him a man without knowledge in this field.", "start": 1366.45, "stop": 1371.84, "duration": 5.39}, {"text": "I submit that Mr. Watkins is an expert.", "start": 1371.84, "stop": 1377.685, "duration": 5.85}, {"text": "He had cooperated with him and he had broken with them and what had he broken with them over?", "start": 1377.685, "stop": 1385.011, "duration": 7.33}, {"text": "Compliance with the very statute, namely the Taft-Hartley Act non-Communist previsions, which if there was to be further legislation would have to be amended or changed or -- or additional provisions provided, not a question.", "start": 1385.011, "stop": 1402.088, "duration": 17.08}, {"text": "And when he said to them as I read the statement, “You do not have the power to engage in this exposure,” their answer was a quotation, a paraphrase of the authorization prevision and as answer you are directed to answer the question.", "start": 1402.088, "stop": 1418.723, "duration": 16.63}, {"text": "In other words, the -- the questioning is clear and therefore, I may have again unduly complicated my case by seeking to provide so much additional evidence of the -- the purpose of exposure.", "start": 1418.723, "stop": 1432.621, "duration": 13.9}, {"text": "In other words, we have in the record and in our brief pages after pages of proof that the House Un-American Activities Committee asserts this independent power of exposure.", "start": 1432.621, "stop": 1447.288, "duration": 14.67}, {"text": "Now, it did seem to me that that was relevant evidence and so to as Judge Edgerton, that the fact that a Committee asserts a power can be considered in determining whether it was exercising that assertive power at a given time.", "start": 1447.288, "stop": 1462.638, "duration": 15.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "How long was he understands throughout?", "start": 1462.638, "stop": 1465.771, "duration": 3.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "There -- I would say that it was -- was an hour about.", "start": 1465.771, "stop": 1470.192, "duration": 4.42}, {"text": "I would say there were intermissions, but I must say --", "start": 1470.192, "stop": 1472.188, "duration": 2}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Or totally an hour.", "start": 1472.188, "stop": 1473.578, "duration": 1.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir, but you see that most of that was -- was asking him to -- to tell about himself.", "start": 1473.578, "stop": 1479.912, "duration": 6.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "But I was going to --", "start": 1479.912, "stop": 1480.82, "duration": 0.91}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "It was about five minutes at the end when this comes up of completeness.", "start": 1480.82, "stop": 1484.591, "duration": 3.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "During that hour's testimony, what was the subject matter of their search into him?", "start": 1484.591, "stop": 1490.547, "duration": 5.96}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "They read him what Rumsey and Spencer, the two previous witnesses had said about him and then probed on whether that was true about him, then they asked him about the --", "start": 1490.547, "stop": 1499.859, "duration": 9.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "And he was forced coming in all of those questions?", "start": 1499.859, "stop": 1501.57, "duration": 1.71}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 1501.57, "stop": 1502.759, "duration": 1.19}, {"text": "That was consistent with his position that he was not ashamed to tell about himself, but he would not turn informant.", "start": 1502.759, "stop": 1508.827, "duration": 6.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "And then they -- is this toward -- you've just indicated this was toward the end of the inquiry?", "start": 1508.827, "stop": 1512.4, "duration": 3.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 1512.4, "stop": 1513.413, "duration": 1.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "And then they asked these questions about these persons --", "start": 1513.413, "stop": 1515.858, "duration": 2.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 1515.858, "stop": 1516.33, "duration": 0.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "And as you've indicated to my earlier question, if he -- when he said, “I won't talk about these people” then they dropped him?", "start": 1516.33, "stop": 1522.035, "duration": 5.71}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir, and he was excused.", "start": 1522.035, "stop": 1523.081, "duration": 1.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Does that summarize that hour?", "start": 1523.081, "stop": 1524.386, "duration": 1.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Precisely.", "start": 1524.386, "stop": 1526.545, "duration": 2.16}, {"text": "Now, getting back to this background material of the House Un-American Activities Committee, the Government's position is that Your Honors cannot consider anything, except the authorizing resolution and the questioning of petitioner.", "start": 1526.545, "stop": 1540.907, "duration": 14.36}, {"text": "Now, I am willing to rest our case on the questioning of petitioner, but I do not see on what theory you should deny yourselves, evidence of an assertive power by the Committee if a man says he‘s going to murder someone else.You can consider that in relation to the fact that there was a death a little later.", "start": 1540.907, "stop": 1559.719, "duration": 18.81}, {"text": "I do not see that there is any difference in this situation.", "start": 1559.719, "stop": 1564.138, "duration": 4.42}, {"text": "Nevertheless, if Your Honor, if -- if the questioning is as clear as I feel, this additional assertive power would not be necessary, but I do feel that Your Honors are -- are free to examine that and it does corroborate and it sort of sets a background that a man has claimed he has the right of exposure, seems to me to set a background when you find questioning which seems so clearly on its face to be exposure.", "start": 1564.138, "stop": 1592.387, "duration": 28.25}, {"text": "Now, what does the Government say in opposition to this overwhelming proof of exposure that we have presented?", "start": 1592.387, "stop": 1599.549, "duration": 7.16}, {"text": "Well, distinguished Solicitor General concedes as I think he must that the Government, that the Committee was not interested in communist techniques in the labor movement, that they had no interest in how the communists were working.", "start": 1599.549, "stop": 1616.386, "duration": 16.84}, {"text": "They come up in this Court for the first time with the following proposition.", "start": 1616.386, "stop": 1622.343, "duration": 5.96}, {"text": "What the committee wanted to know was the mathematically exact number of communists in the labor movement in the middle 1940s to be determined by naming and numbering every one of the players.", "start": 1622.343, "stop": 1635.604, "duration": 13.26}, {"text": "Now, that is the position as I understand it of the Government here that the Committee's purpose was to find the exact number of communists in middle 1940s by getting the names of each one and holding them.", "start": 1635.604, "stop": 1650.639, "duration": 15.03}, {"text": "Now, I sympathize.", "start": 1650.639, "stop": 1652.531, "duration": 1.89}, {"text": "All I'm asking with the Government that they had a hard problem of finding a legislative purpose from questioning like this, but I do say that it attacks all our ability to believe, to think that a Committee was seeking to make a retroactive census of the communists in the middle 1940's.", "start": 1652.531, "stop": 1675.287, "duration": 22.76}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is there any proof that the Committee already had these names?", "start": 1675.287, "stop": 1678.724, "duration": 3.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, yes sir.", "start": 1678.724, "stop": 1679.824, "duration": 1.1}, {"text": "They had the names from Rumsey and Spencer, but I'm not suggesting the Committee that that's a proof that they were in fact communists.", "start": 1679.824, "stop": 1688.644, "duration": 8.82}, {"text": "What the Committee was doing here was really trying to make a legislative trial of each one of these people to determine whether they were communist.", "start": 1688.644, "stop": 1696.852, "duration": 8.21}, {"text": "They had the names, but that alone doesn't determine whether they were communist or not, for example Mr. Watkins himself, they had his name.Now, he says he testified under oath he wasn't a communist.", "start": 1696.852, "stop": 1708.841, "duration": 11.99}, {"text": "What they were doing was taking all these names and then running a sort of a legislative trial over each one these.", "start": 1708.841, "stop": 1715.807, "duration": 6.97}, {"text": "Now, the Government doesn't suggest, if Your Honor please, how this mathematically exact number of communists in the mid-1940's in the labor movement would help them with any legislation, that they say that was the purpose of the Committee, was to find this mathematically perfect number.", "start": 1715.807, "stop": 1735.056, "duration": 19.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "It might indicate the -- the size of the magnitude of the problem.", "start": 1735.056, "stop": 1738.254, "duration": 3.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "It -- it would indicate the magnitude of the problem back in 1945, but the Committee, however, never suggested that that was their purpose and indeed and I think this is -- this would really to settle the point.", "start": 1738.254, "stop": 1751.927, "duration": 13.67}, {"text": "Indeed, the committee didn't say to Mr. Watkins, “How many communists were there then?”", "start": 1751.927, "stop": 1759.95, "duration": 8.02}, {"text": "They didn't say to Mr. Watkins, “Can you name any other communists there?”", "start": 1759.95, "stop": 1765.587, "duration": 5.64}, {"text": "They clearly were not engaged in trying to find this retroactive sense.", "start": 1765.587, "stop": 1770.368, "duration": 4.78}, {"text": "Of course, they could have got it from the F.B.I., I suppose.", "start": 1770.368, "stop": 1773.099, "duration": 2.73}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Am I wrong in having the impression that Mr. Hoover almost annually gives us a statical account?", "start": 1773.099, "stop": 1778.63, "duration": 5.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, you're quite right, if Your Honor please and just how long ago we had that, I'm not very clear, but nowhere as it suggest that how the mathematically precise number of communists and labor movement in middle 1940s will help you pass legislation in 1954, when you don't even asked about the statutes that either intervened and when the middle 1940s where a period of what you might call a -- a friendliness towards the communist movement and then on middle 1950s of the exact opposite.", "start": 1778.63, "stop": 1809.679, "duration": 31.05}, {"text": "It was trying to find the census at time which wouldn't be helpful to determine your action at a -- at a later date.", "start": 1809.679, "stop": 1817.246, "duration": 7.57}, {"text": "And as I say, the Committee never suggested this was their purpose.", "start": 1817.246, "stop": 1820.515, "duration": 3.27}, {"text": "Their action show it wasn't their purpose because they didn't ask him how many there were.", "start": 1820.515, "stop": 1825.178, "duration": 4.66}, {"text": "So -- well, to come to the Government's other contention of why this was an exposure, it is a fact and I call Your Honor's attention to the opening statement of the Chairman of the Committee at page 43 and 44 of the record.", "start": 1825.178, "stop": 1844.308, "duration": 19.13}, {"text": "Now, in a two-page lengthy opening statement, this was six weeks before petitioner testified in Washington.", "start": 1844.308, "stop": 1852.442, "duration": 8.13}, {"text": "This was the opening statement in Chicago six weeks before, but in the opening statement in Washington, they refer back to this.", "start": 1852.442, "stop": 1860.323, "duration": 7.88}, {"text": "This is a -- what you might call a gently causing statement about the past activities of the -- of the Committee.", "start": 1860.323, "stop": 1868.508, "duration": 8.18}, {"text": "And there is a reference in this statement on -- in this opening statement on Page 44 to a bill.", "start": 1868.508, "stop": 1877.14, "duration": 8.63}, {"text": "This is the second paragraph on page 44, to a bill which would deprive Communist infiltrated labor unions of the facilities of the MLRB.", "start": 1877.14, "stop": 1895.252, "duration": 18.11}, {"text": "Now, if your Honors please, that bill was enacted or rather another bill was enacted but on that same subject.", "start": 1895.252, "stop": 1906.403, "duration": 11.15}, {"text": "Now, here is an opening statement telling all about your activities.", "start": 1906.403, "stop": 1911.27, "duration": 4.87}, {"text": "Immediately thereafter, they go into all other sponsor activities, communist at farms, communists in the Government and all other activities.", "start": 1911.27, "stop": 1919.409, "duration": 8.14}, {"text": "And then, they come to this fellow, Watkins, and they asked him questions that haven't any relation whatever to this bill.", "start": 1919.409, "stop": 1927.84, "duration": 8.43}, {"text": "And yet, they say because this bill was mentioned, therefore, a question that has no relationship whatever to the Bill is in some way to be protected.", "start": 1927.84, "stop": 1940.073, "duration": 12.23}, {"text": "Now, it maybe, it may very well be that if the Bill haven't been mentioned, the questioning still could have been about something that might produce legislation.", "start": 1940.073, "stop": 1951.689, "duration": 11.62}, {"text": "But the fact that the bill is mentioned, if the questioning is wholly unrelated in any way to the possibilities of that bill, the bill itself is not determinative or relevant.", "start": 1951.689, "stop": 1963.887, "duration": 12.2}, {"text": "Indeed, I think the best way I could put it is that the dependency of legislation is not a hunting license to engage in exposure where the questions have no relation to that legislation and there it seems to me again the -- the case rest.", "start": 1963.887, "stop": 1983.549, "duration": 19.66}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now, suppose I put the most favorable aspect on this as I think one must.", "start": 1983.549, "stop": 1989.137, "duration": 5.59}, {"text": "Suppose when he refused to answer the inquiry about the first -- when the first name was put then, the Chairman has then said to Mr. Watkins.", "start": 1989.137, "stop": 1999.528, "duration": 10.39}, {"text": "“Let me read you what I said in March in Chicago as to why this Committee is here.", "start": 1999.528, "stop": 2005.846, "duration": 6.32}, {"text": "And in connection with that, I now repeat my question, please tell us about Mr. Smith.", "start": 2005.846, "stop": 2010.138, "duration": 4.29}, {"text": "What difference would that make in your case?", "start": 2010.138, "stop": 2012.151, "duration": 2.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I think it would have made very little in that.", "start": 2012.151, "stop": 2014.48, "duration": 2.33}, {"text": "I think Mr. Watkins could rightly have said, “I don't understand the relationship between the two.”", "start": 2014.48, "stop": 2019.201, "duration": 4.72}, {"text": "If one has been given him, I think maybe he would have had to answer, but it's significant that when you have this man who had been in the very peak of a fight over this kind of a statute, they weren't interested in anything about it.", "start": 2019.201, "stop": 2033.885, "duration": 14.68}, {"text": "And therefore, I say it's perfectly clear that they weren't interested in the bill.", "start": 2033.885, "stop": 2038.291, "duration": 4.41}, {"text": "It seems to me, if Your Honors please, if we -- that exposure -- it probably is a -- in many cases, it's going to be a hard thing to prove.", "start": 2038.291, "stop": 2049.667, "duration": 11.38}, {"text": "There's always the possibility of retroactive rationalization and that's exactly what we've had here.", "start": 2049.667, "stop": 2057.001, "duration": 7.33}, {"text": "But now, the Committee didn't tell us they had any such purpose.", "start": 2057.001, "stop": 2062.043, "duration": 5.04}, {"text": "This wasn't the purpose in the lower court.", "start": 2062.043, "stop": 2064.371, "duration": 2.33}, {"text": "Indeed, I'd like to call Your Honor's attention that this new suggestion of the Government that they were trying to get a retroactive census of the names of every Communist in the mid-1940s in the labor movement was as late as their brief and opposition only a hypothetical possibility.", "start": 2064.371, "stop": 2085.004, "duration": 20.63}, {"text": "On page 5 of our reply brief, I quote from the Government's brief in opposition where the Government says, “If the Committee had the additional and more general way of ascertaining the number of communists at a particular period on a recent history, that too would be a valid subject of inquiry.”", "start": 2085.004, "stop": 2104.316, "duration": 19.31}, {"text": "In other words, what the Government now says is the subject of inquiry.", "start": 2104.316, "stop": 2108.361, "duration": 4.05}, {"text": "They had this latest brief in our position simply suggest it was a hypothetical possibility as to the subject of inquiry.", "start": 2108.361, "stop": 2116.506, "duration": 8.14}, {"text": "Well, if Your Honors please, it seems to be that -- that we have shown a purpose of exposure and that in light with Your Honor, Mr. Justice Frankfurter has suggested himself the -- on the constitutional aspect of this, that would end the case.", "start": 2116.506, "stop": 2135.418, "duration": 18.91}, {"text": "I personally was prepared to rest the case on those two points.", "start": 2135.418, "stop": 2140.679, "duration": 5.26}, {"text": "However, I remember the discomfiture of counsel in Peters v. Hobby for not arguing the narrower grounds of a -- I wish the Court might rest a decision and seeking to be put in the position of seeking to force a constitutional issue and I have no desire to get in that position.", "start": 2140.679, "stop": 2162.54, "duration": 21.86}, {"text": "And therefore, we have -- we do contend, if Your Honors please, that the -- these questions are not within the authorizing resolution, that of course being a narrower ground of decision than a serious constitutional issue of separation of powers that we have raised.", "start": 2162.54, "stop": 2177.874, "duration": 15.33}, {"text": "Now, there are two possible grounds of interpretation of the congressional -- authorizing resolution, which would take the questioning of petitioner outside of that resolution.", "start": 2177.874, "stop": 2191.522, "duration": 13.65}, {"text": "First, that there was no intent by Congress to give the Committee a power of exposure, and if Your Honors will examine the resolution, it's in the record.", "start": 2191.522, "stop": 2205.347, "duration": 13.83}, {"text": "It's in the briefs of many places.", "start": 2205.347, "stop": 2207.016, "duration": 1.67}, {"text": "It's in our brief at page 4 of our -- of the initial white petitioner's brief.", "start": 2207.016, "stop": 2213.4, "duration": 6.38}, {"text": "You will notice that the purpose that deals with the extent character and objects of Un-American Activities and subversive propaganda.", "start": 2213.4, "stop": 2221.324, "duration": 7.92}, {"text": "And three, all other questions in relation thereto that would aid Congress in any necessary remedial legislation.", "start": 2221.324, "stop": 2229.067, "duration": 7.74}, {"text": "It does seem to us three that those words in any necessary remedial legislation are -- cover both one and two as well as three and therefore, there was no power of exposure given.", "start": 2229.067, "stop": 2243.817, "duration": 14.75}, {"text": "And therefore, if our proof is correct on the exposure point, Your Honors would -- could by interpretation of the resolution accomplish the same result as I have argued under the Constitution.", "start": 2243.817, "stop": 2258.466, "duration": 14.65}, {"text": "Secondly, however, and I think it's even clearer if Your Honors please, this -- to summarize this resolution in a sentence, it's a power to investigate Un-American and subversive propaganda activities.", "start": 2258.466, "stop": 2272.115, "duration": 13.65}, {"text": "Now, where in subversive and Un-American Propaganda Activity, you find an authority to ask a man to name certain persons as Communists in 1945?", "start": 2272.115, "stop": 2287.017, "duration": 14.9}, {"text": "In other words, it seems to us that on that narrowest ground, we are outside of the resolution.", "start": 2287.017, "stop": 2294.495, "duration": 7.48}, {"text": "Now, I would be less than candid if I did not say that that over simplifies the problem, because for the last 20 years, the House Committee has been doing what we are here complaining of to the public knowledge of everyone and to the knowledge of the members of the house who have reenacted the resolution, who have given them appropriations and who -- one could argue have ratified what they have been doing.", "start": 2294.495, "stop": 2326.278, "duration": 31.78}, {"text": "And it was because of the ratification point that I preferred to rely on the constitutional argument.", "start": 2326.278, "stop": 2333.525, "duration": 7.25}, {"text": "But again, referring to our duty to find the narrowest ground, I would say to Your Honors that there is a serious question whether Congress could ratify so broad a change in the meaning of the resolution as it's necessary to cover the situation here.", "start": 2333.525, "stop": 2351.353, "duration": 17.83}, {"text": "In other words, there are decisions of this Court that what you can ratify is only a reasonable interpretation of a resolution and that this interpretation to broaden the words, propaganda and propaganda activities to cover identification of all Communists in mid-1940s, let us say is beyond a reasonable broadening of those words and I --", "start": 2351.353, "stop": 2375.235, "duration": 23.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "When you said this Court, have we had any case?", "start": 2375.235, "stop": 2377.67, "duration": 2.43}, {"text": "Have we decided any case in which we carried over a doctrine of ratification by subsequent legislation in the sense that whatever any Committee did under any prior resolution was read into incorporated by reference as though it specifically approved of every action taken by a prior Committee, anything like that?", "start": 2377.67, "stop": 2400.366, "duration": 22.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "No sir.", "start": 2400.366, "stop": 2400.833, "duration": 0.47}, {"text": "I was --", "start": 2400.833, "stop": 2401.084, "duration": 0.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "So, I'm recalled to --", "start": 2401.084, "stop": 2401.974, "duration": 0.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "No.", "start": 2401.974, "stop": 2402.24, "duration": 0.27}, {"text": "I was referring, sir, to the tax cases where words --", "start": 2402.24, "stop": 2404.374, "duration": 2.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that's --", "start": 2404.374, "stop": 2405.733, "duration": 1.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I was --", "start": 2405.733, "stop": 2406.166, "duration": 0.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "The specific rulings on a specific situation with a specific adjudication.", "start": 2406.166, "stop": 2412.598, "duration": 6.43}, {"text": "Even that caused a good deal of imagination to assume that Congress knows all about it or that reenacts it.", "start": 2412.598, "stop": 2418.115, "duration": 5.52}, {"text": "But in all events, that's a very different situation.", "start": 2418.115, "stop": 2419.757, "duration": 1.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "I -- I agree.", "start": 2419.757, "stop": 2420.857, "duration": 1.1}, {"text": "I was simply using those cases to show they don't go this far, Your Honor, since they know that the only thing you can ratify is the reasonably -- is a reasonable interpretation, whereas I'm suggesting that this goes beyond that.", "start": 2420.857, "stop": 2433.37, "duration": 12.51}, {"text": "And therefore, if Your Honor should agree that the ratification has not occurred here, then I would suggest that that is narrowest ground of decision on which this case can turn.", "start": 2433.37, "stop": 2444.356, "duration": 10.99}, {"text": "Now, to turn briefly for just a moment to the protections of the First Amendment.", "start": 2444.356, "stop": 2451.205, "duration": 6.85}, {"text": "If as we contend most strongly and certainly, there was -- the Committee was engaged in the activity of exposure, there was also a violation of the First Amendment, because if its purpose was exposure, then there is no possible legislative need to justify the obvious repressive effect of the activities of the Committee.", "start": 2451.205, "stop": 2477.662, "duration": 26.46}, {"text": "But I am assuming here in arguing the First Amendment point that the Committee had a legislative purpose, but I have been found to be wrong in arguing that it did not have and that it had a legislative purpose.", "start": 2477.662, "stop": 2492.45, "duration": 14.79}, {"text": "And we nevertheless contend strongly that this was a violation of the First Amendment.", "start": 2492.45, "stop": 2499.566, "duration": 7.12}, {"text": "Legislative purpose is not legislative need.", "start": 2499.566, "stop": 2503.267, "duration": 3.7}, {"text": "You still must balance the repressive effects of the activities of the Committee on speech and association against the need for the legislation.", "start": 2503.267, "stop": 2514.117, "duration": 10.85}, {"text": "I -- I take it as what the Rumely case has told us.", "start": 2514.117, "stop": 2518.693, "duration": 4.58}, {"text": "Now, this Court has told us there must be a way, but it has not told us the standards for weighing and that will have to be worked out as we go along.", "start": 2518.693, "stop": 2526.967, "duration": 8.27}, {"text": "I take it that the clear and present danger test hardly fits exactly this kind of a weighing situation, but it does remind us of the importance of protecting the right of speech and association from congressional activities.", "start": 2526.967, "stop": 2543.165, "duration": 16.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Rauh, you strongly urged the relevance of the announced purpose of the Committee as shedding light on or rate -- illuminating what they actually did.", "start": 2543.165, "stop": 2556.892, "duration": 13.73}, {"text": "You argued that if a man says, “this is my purpose,” and then something happens would you bail out that purpose that that colors then qualifies.", "start": 2556.892, "stop": 2567.412, "duration": 10.52}, {"text": "But you haven't -- perhaps you want to rest it on the briefs and so, I'd like to know what -- what is the basis for your saying that they announced that they're engaged in a process of exposing?", "start": 2567.412, "stop": 2581.739, "duration": 14.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I thought I can rest --", "start": 2581.739, "stop": 2582.84, "duration": 1.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "What's your answer to that --", "start": 2582.84, "stop": 2584.04, "duration": 1.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "I can rest it on brief, sir on page --", "start": 2584.04, "stop": 2586.34, "duration": 2.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- did this Committee, to this -- the Chairman of this Committee make any such statement?", "start": 2586.34, "stop": 2589.545, "duration": 3.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 2589.545, "stop": 2590.736, "duration": 1.19}, {"text": "We summarized this from pages 41 to 58 of our brief.", "start": 2590.736, "stop": 2598.211, "duration": 7.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- you state what you regard as the most unequivocal assertion --", "start": 2598.211, "stop": 2601.072, "duration": 2.86}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I -- I --", "start": 2601.072, "stop": 2601.795, "duration": 0.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- by this Chairman.", "start": 2601.795, "stop": 2604.492, "duration": 2.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Velde, the Chairman of the Committee, I'm now quoting -- I'm now looking for Judge Edgerton's dissent that that Mr. Velde, the Chairman of the Committee in the 83rd Congress who presided the Watkins hearing cited in another hearing, “We feel that we have a duty and that duty has been imposed upon by Congress not only to report to the people for the purpose of remedial legislation, but to inform the people who elected us about subversive activities.”", "start": 2604.492, "stop": 2628.742, "duration": 24.25}, {"text": "Now, there is --", "start": 2628.742, "stop": 2629.116, "duration": 0.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "There's a speech that he made?", "start": 2629.116, "stop": 2630.598, "duration": 1.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 2630.598, "stop": 2631.486, "duration": 0.89}, {"text": "Well, now, I'm hearing before the Committee on Un-American activities.", "start": 2631.486, "stop": 2635.037, "duration": 3.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "I mean -- and -- and his role as Chairman.", "start": 2635.037, "stop": 2637.07, "duration": 2.03}, {"text": "He wasn't addressing --", "start": 2637.07, "stop": 2638.234, "duration": 1.16}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 2638.234, "stop": 2638.53, "duration": 0.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- his -- his enthusiast in Chicago.", "start": 2638.53, "stop": 2641.223, "duration": 2.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 2641.223, "stop": 2641.655, "duration": 0.43}, {"text": "The Government suggests that these are a lot of speeches.", "start": 2641.655, "stop": 2644.695, "duration": 3.04}, {"text": "These are all reports and here are on -- we did include some speeches, but the bulk of it are reports and hearings and statements on the Board of Congress in the capacity of the Commerce, but I do suggest that I -- we have --", "start": 2644.695, "stop": 2659.441, "duration": 14.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "All right.", "start": 2659.441, "stop": 2659.622, "duration": 0.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Joseph L. Rauh, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- made an overwhelming showing of this on pages 41 to 58 of our brief.", "start": 2659.622, "stop": 2664.243, "duration": 4.62}, {"text": "And back to the question of the First Amendment, if Your Honors please, what we have to weigh here is the repressive effect of the Committee against the need for the legislation.", "start": 2664.243, "stop": 2674.085, "duration": 9.84}, {"text": "Now, if Your Honors please, the repressive effect is clear.", "start": 2674.085, "stop": 2679.407, "duration": 5.32}, {"text": "To call a man before a Committee and humiliate him into being an informer and to take out all of his past, it's a -- it's a public humiliation for past exercise of speech and association.", "start": 2679.407, "stop": 2691.55, "duration": 12.14}, {"text": "It's also a prior restraint on himself and on others for the future.", "start": 2691.55, "stop": 2696.102, "duration": 4.55}, {"text": "And what need is asserted to say that this repressive effect should be allowed by this Court that they wanted to make a retroactive census of Communist at a different period in our history when that very activity was not considered wrongful and get that retroactive census in order.", "start": 2696.102, "stop": 2714.824, "duration": 18.72}, {"text": "That's the need to be weighed against this repressive effect.", "start": 2714.824, "stop": 2718.282, "duration": 3.46}, {"text": "I suggest to Your Honors that there is no way that that can be balanced anyway, except in the direction of freedom.", "start": 2718.282, "stop": 2727.075, "duration": 8.79}, {"text": "And finally, we argue that this resolution is too vague and indefinite to stand under the cases that hold that a defendant has a right to a reasonably and ascertainable standard of guilt before he maybe prosecuted.", "start": 2727.075, "stop": 2742.344, "duration": 15.27}, {"text": "What this investigation says -- what this - or resolution says is that the Committee has the authority to investigate Un-American and subversive propaganda activities.", "start": 2742.344, "stop": 2755.192, "duration": 12.85}, {"text": "Was petitioner to know that when he was asked about people in 1945, whether they were members of the Party that that was propaganda, that that was subversive, that that was Un-American, I would challenge anybody to suggest that different people sitting in that chair would not reach different conclusion.", "start": 2755.192, "stop": 2773.262, "duration": 18.07}, {"text": "And what does the government say?", "start": 2773.262, "stop": 2775.269, "duration": 2.01}, {"text": "They say that all resolutions of Congress are too vague to meet the standard.", "start": 2775.269, "stop": 2780.258, "duration": 4.99}, {"text": "They rely on the fact that if you hold them up to the standard of a -- of a criminal statute, then they will not be able, Congress will not be able to do its job.", "start": 2780.258, "stop": 2790.085, "duration": 9.83}, {"text": "I suggest they forget that in the House -- House of Representatives today, there are only three committees that exercise this power.", "start": 2790.085, "stop": 2799.943, "duration": 9.86}, {"text": "Whatever vagueness you may want to have in Congress for internal functioning of the body is one thing, but when they seek to use the subpoena power and to prosecute people for violation, certainly, they must live up to the standards of the (Inaudible) Grocery case.", "start": 2799.943, "stop": 2817.558, "duration": 17.61}, {"text": "It is one thing if they call a witness before the bar of the House when he gets a last clear chance to answer.", "start": 2817.558, "stop": 2825.136, "duration": 7.58}, {"text": "But when they use their criminal prosecutions, the criminal process to prosecute a man, then he must have a reasonably ascertainable standard of guilt.", "start": 2825.136, "stop": 2836.081, "duration": 10.95}, {"text": "Finally, there is involved in the case, the same grand jury point that (Inaudible) when we have briefed it fully.", "start": 2836.081, "stop": 2844.966, "duration": 8.88}, {"text": "I would prefer because I do not believe the Court would likely get to this point to reserve my time for rebuttal.", "start": 2844.966, "stop": 2851.688, "duration": 6.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Okay.", "start": 2851.688, "stop": 2853.501, "duration": 1.81}, {"text": "Mr. Solicitor General.", "start": 2853.501, "stop": 2856.313, "duration": 2.81}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "May it please the Court.", "start": 2856.313, "stop": 2862.906, "duration": 6.59}, {"text": "I should like to call your attention first to one -- one statement in the briefs that I should like to clarify in regard to the decision of the Court of Appeals.", "start": 2862.906, "stop": 2879.572, "duration": 16.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "In your brief or the other brief?", "start": 2879.572, "stop": 2881.459, "duration": 1.89}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's in the other brief and it's in regard to whether the Court of Appeals found that there was a legislative purpose in the questions that were asked and counsel in the brief recite that the Court merely said that there could have been such a legislative purpose.", "start": 2881.459, "stop": 2905.617, "duration": 24.16}, {"text": "On page 178 of the record, the Court said, “The questions asked Watkins could be asked for a valid legislative purpose.\"", "start": 2905.617, "stop": 2918.033, "duration": 12.42}, {"text": "Then, if you will go on to the bottom of the page, the same page, you'll find that the Court said, “A majority of the Court gives out the opinion that the questions were pertinent to a valid legislative purpose and were authorized by the Act.”", "start": 2918.033, "stop": 2938.989, "duration": 20.96}, {"text": "Now, from what the Court has heard, it must be difficult to understand how anyone could say that there could be a valid legislative purpose in the questions that were asked.", "start": 2938.989, "stop": 2952.017, "duration": 13.03}, {"text": "And so, if you will bear with me briefly, I'd like to go back to the evidence and see what there was before this Committee upon which they could ask such questions that would show a valid legislative purpose to six out of eight common judges of the Court of Appeals.", "start": 2952.017, "stop": 2971.032, "duration": 19.02}, {"text": "This appearance was a continuance of a prior hearing that started in Chicago.", "start": 2971.032, "stop": 2977.726, "duration": 6.69}, {"text": "And the petitioner was asked whether he knew of the testimony of two of the other witness, prior witnesses, Mr. Rumsey and Mr. Spencer and he said he was familiar with it.", "start": 2977.726, "stop": 3002.595, "duration": 24.87}, {"text": "And what did they testified to?", "start": 3002.595, "stop": 3006.218, "duration": 3.62}, {"text": "Mr. Rumsey said he was recruited into the Communist Party by the petitioner that at the beginning he paid dues to him being the petitioner.", "start": 3006.218, "stop": 3018.43, "duration": 12.21}, {"text": "Later, he collected dues from the petitioner who assumed the alias of Sam Brown.", "start": 3018.43, "stop": 3031.073, "duration": 12.64}, {"text": "Then, the Committee asked many questions of Mr. Rumsey.", "start": 3031.073, "stop": 3040.649, "duration": 9.58}, {"text": "And amongst them, he asked about the infiltration of the Communist Party into this union.", "start": 3040.649, "stop": 3052.674, "duration": 12.03}, {"text": "Two of the questions are particular of interest with regard to a valid legislative purpose.", "start": 3052.674, "stop": 3058.554, "duration": 5.88}, {"text": "On page 138, close to the bottom of the page, statement of Mr. Rumsey in answering the question.", "start": 3058.554, "stop": 3069.022, "duration": 10.47}, {"text": "I'll read the question first.", "start": 3069.022, "stop": 3070.553, "duration": 1.53}, {"text": "“Mr. Rumsey what was it?", "start": 3070.553, "stop": 3072.403, "duration": 1.85}, {"text": "What you -- would you describe to the Committee the main purpose and activities of that branch of the Party?", "start": 3072.403, "stop": 3079.613, "duration": 7.21}, {"text": "What were they trying to do for the Communist Party?”", "start": 3079.613, "stop": 3083.604, "duration": 3.99}, {"text": "Mr. Rumsey, “Well what they were striving to do was to disrupt mainly to set their program of propaganda to get the shop workers acclimated to the daily worker and that was the function of the organizer.”", "start": 3083.604, "stop": 3101.352, "duration": 17.75}, {"text": "Then, there's other testimony about how things were being done and on page 139 and about the same general point on the page, Mr. (Inaudible), “Could you tell us specifically what your duties were as organizer for the Communist Party?”", "start": 3101.352, "stop": 3119.347, "duration": 18}, {"text": "That was to Mr. Rumsey.", "start": 3119.347, "stop": 3121.299, "duration": 1.95}, {"text": "Mr. Rumsey answered, “Well, to recruit and to recruit new members, hold study groups, clubs as they called it, study clubs in the evenings and then as I say, keep our people in the shop what communist we had to lead the union meetings and dominate them.”", "start": 3121.299, "stop": 3148.804, "duration": 27.51}, {"text": "Then, Spencer said he recruited -- was recruited in the Communist Party by Rumsey with the endorsement of this petitioner as well as if prior approval.", "start": 3148.804, "stop": 3162.563, "duration": 13.76}, {"text": "Petitioner was then the Vice President of the Farm Equipment CIO and he said he attended Communist Party meeting at which the petitioner and two others, Kate Hall and Jerry Field were present.", "start": 3162.563, "stop": 3180.467, "duration": 17.9}, {"text": "Then, the petitioner described his official position with the union.", "start": 3180.467, "stop": 3184.197, "duration": 3.73}, {"text": "He was one of the important officers during this period at which time the evidence is clear from these other witnesses that this union was infiltrated by the Communist Party.", "start": 3184.197, "stop": 3197.092, "duration": 12.89}, {"text": "Petitioner admitted knowing Rumsey and Spencer and was familiar with their testimony concerning him.", "start": 3197.092, "stop": 3205.036, "duration": 7.94}, {"text": "He admitted that he cooperated with the Communist Party and having “participated in Communist activities during 1942 to 1947,” to such a degree that some persons may honest believe -- honestly believe we too have been a Party member.", "start": 3205.036, "stop": 3224.932, "duration": 19.9}, {"text": "He admitted making contributions to the communist causes, signed petitions for their various causes, attended coxes at a convention of the union at which Communist Party officials were present.", "start": 3224.932, "stop": 3240.652, "duration": 15.72}, {"text": "He participated in the union meetings with the Communist (Inaudible), attended public meetings of the Communist Party at which William Z. Foster then president spoke.", "start": 3240.652, "stop": 3256.028, "duration": 15.38}, {"text": "He also testified that he was aware that -- that there was a general program policy of the Communist Party to attempt to control the various unions and testified it was quote “Probably correct to say that the discussions he had with them, individuals known by him to be communist had been in connection with their desire to control the union's policy and activities.”", "start": 3256.028, "stop": 3288.159, "duration": 32.13}, {"text": "Already denied that he had been a card carrying member of the Communist Party.", "start": 3288.159, "stop": 3296.046, "duration": 7.89}, {"text": "He contradicted both Spencer and Rumsey and said he had nothing to do with recruiting men.", "start": 3296.046, "stop": 3306.403, "duration": 10.36}, {"text": "He said that Spencer was wrong when he termed any meetings which the petitioner attended as closed Communist Party meetings.", "start": 3306.403, "stop": 3317.299, "duration": 10.9}, {"text": "He contradicted Rumsey and denied having recruited Rumsey or receiving dues from him or paying dues to him under the alias of Sam Brown.", "start": 3317.299, "stop": 3333.946, "duration": 16.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is that relevant to our question?", "start": 3333.946, "stop": 3336.128, "duration": 2.18}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, because of this.", "start": 3336.128, "stop": 3338.664, "duration": 2.54}, {"text": "It shows that there was an inquiry to this man about the question of infiltrating unions for communist purposes.", "start": 3338.664, "stop": 3349.092, "duration": 10.43}, {"text": "The -- the Congress within four months after this in the Communist Control Act of 1954 passed an amendment to the Internal Security Act of 1950 in which it provided with regard to unions which had been infiltrated and took away from their opportunity to have the benefits of the NLRA.", "start": 3349.092, "stop": 3375.975, "duration": 26.88}, {"text": "So that Congress was inquiring at this very moment about that from this very petitioner, obtained information from him that he knew that that was what was happening in that very union, that the Communist Party was actively engaged in this very activity.", "start": 3375.975, "stop": 3394.264, "duration": 18.29}, {"text": "They then proceed to legislate about it and they were inquiring about it at the time to determine about the legislation.", "start": 3394.264, "stop": 3401.858, "duration": 7.59}, {"text": "Now, when they asked him about these things, the evidence also shows that everyone of these people that they asked him about, they had asked Rumsey and Spencer about prior to that and Rumsey and Spencer has said that they were members of the Communist Party.", "start": 3401.858, "stop": 3421.905, "duration": 20.05}, {"text": "And they had also asked as I have shown, Rumsey and Spencer about propaganda activities, the efforts of the Communist Party to infiltrate this very union and what they knew about it.", "start": 3421.905, "stop": 3434.708, "duration": 12.8}, {"text": "Now, this witness comes there and he said -- he denies the testimony of Rumsey and Spencer with regard to himself and Rumsey and Spencer in this very proceeding at Chicago had been asked about some 25 to 30 different persons whether they were communist.", "start": 3434.708, "stop": 3457.799, "duration": 23.09}, {"text": "And Rumsey and Spencer said that everyone was.", "start": 3457.799, "stop": 3462.248, "duration": 4.45}, {"text": "Here, this man says, “I wasn't a Communist.", "start": 3462.248, "stop": 3466.539, "duration": 4.29}, {"text": "I did a lot of things like people might think I was a communist, but I wasn't.”", "start": 3466.539, "stop": 3472.341, "duration": 5.8}, {"text": "He apparently had knowledge in regard to this union.", "start": 3472.341, "stop": 3476.342, "duration": 4}, {"text": "He was an officer of it.", "start": 3476.342, "stop": 3477.77, "duration": 1.43}, {"text": "He cooperated with the communist and then very active.", "start": 3477.77, "stop": 3482.079, "duration": 4.31}, {"text": "Now, if you could find any place that was more ideal to try to discover facts upon which Congress could act knowledge -- knowledgeably, I'd like to know what it could be.", "start": 3482.079, "stop": 3495.797, "duration": 13.72}, {"text": "Here, in this very union, in this very thing that Congress was looking for had happened.", "start": 3495.797, "stop": 3501.406, "duration": 5.61}, {"text": "They had infiltrated, this man was part of it and these witnesses that testified to his participation and to the other activities and how they did it, by propaganda and the common methods of the Communist Party.", "start": 3501.406, "stop": 3517.728, "duration": 16.32}, {"text": "Then, they come to him and they asked him.", "start": 3517.728, "stop": 3520.483, "duration": 2.76}, {"text": "He says, “I'm not a Communist,” and he says, “These men might have thought so, but I'm not,” and he questioned their testimony about receiving dues or whether a man was a Communist or not.", "start": 3520.483, "stop": 3533.654, "duration": 13.17}, {"text": "It might be a question that is difficult and his explanation of the fact, “That I acted like a Communist.", "start": 3533.654, "stop": 3541.312, "duration": 7.66}, {"text": "I cooperated with them.", "start": 3541.312, "stop": 3542.823, "duration": 1.51}, {"text": "I did things from which people might infer or conclude I was a Communist,” might be answer to that.", "start": 3542.823, "stop": 3548.888, "duration": 6.07}, {"text": "But when you get down to the question of whether or not he paid dues and received dues, that's a question of fact that would be hard to be wrong about.", "start": 3548.888, "stop": 3558.979, "duration": 10.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Solicitor, may I ask merely to search the record.", "start": 3558.979, "stop": 3564.849, "duration": 5.87}, {"text": "Are you implying or is it to be implied that in his resistances, he was exculpatory of himself?", "start": 3564.849, "stop": 3571.627, "duration": 6.78}, {"text": "Was there any suggestion that he was evasive or trying to get from under in answering any questions that might put him in an -- if you please, undesirable or questionable life?", "start": 3571.627, "stop": 3584.109, "duration": 12.48}, {"text": "Did he show any invasion about his -- in the -- I read the record that's why I'm asking you (Voice Overlap)?", "start": 3584.109, "stop": 3588.651, "duration": 4.54}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, the only thing that could be --", "start": 3588.651, "stop": 3591.255, "duration": 2.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Whereas all the shield in order to prevent further exploration of his incite?", "start": 3591.255, "stop": 3598.525, "duration": 7.27}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "The only way that could be construed that way, I think, would be the fact that he denied this expressed testimony of these other witnesses in regard to this inquiry.", "start": 3598.525, "stop": 3608.827, "duration": 10.3}, {"text": "And it seems to me that if reasonable that anyone who was making such an examination either in Court or in a congressional committee where the committee members may or not have the same experience that lawyers have in dealing with witnesses that when the witness starts to deny the testimony, not only of whether he was a Communist, but whether he had paid and received money as dues in the Communist Party that they had a right to go into that further.", "start": 3608.827, "stop": 3643.243, "duration": 34.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "We'll hear the rest of it after --", "start": 3643.243, "stop": 3645.551, "duration": 2.31}]}]}], "decidedBy": "Warren Court", "arguedOn": "Mar 7, 1957", "petitioner": "John Watkins", "respondent": "United States", "docket": "261", "citation": "354 US 178 (1957)", "justiaLink": "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/354/178", "lowerCourt": "United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit", "grantedOn": "", "decidedOn": "Jun 17, 1957", "wikiData": {"title": "Watkins v. United States", "Litigants": "Watkins v. United States", "ArgueDate": "March 7", "ArgueYear": "1957", "DecideDate": "June 17", "DecideYear": "1957", "FullName": "John T. Watkins v. United States", "ParallelCitations": "77 S. Ct. 1173; 1 [[Lawyers' Edition|L. Ed. 2d]] 1273; 1957 [[LexisNexis|U.S. LEXIS]] 1558; 76 Ohio L. Abs. 225", "USVol": "354", "USPage": "178", "Prior": "", "Subsequent": "", "Holding": "Watkins was unable to determine his obligation to respond to questions posed to him and so was denied due process.", "SCOTUS": "1957-1958", "Majority": "Warren", "JoinMajority": "Black, Frankfurter, Douglas, Harlan, Brennan", "Concurrence": "Frankfurter", "Dissent": "Clark", "NotParticipating": "Burton, Whittaker"}}